<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Dives to New Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Europe's single currency took
another dive Monday after Finland's Finance Minister Sauli
Niinisto said there were "quite natural reasons" for the
currency's weakness against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the start of a meeting of finance ministers from
the euro zone's 11 countries, Niinisto blamed the state of the
European Union economy for the currency's troubles, saying that
"we are not doing so well as they are doing in the (United) States
with the economy."
</P>
<P>
Following his statement, the dollar gained again, setting a new
record high against the single currency, before dropping a 10th of
a cent again. In London on Monday afternoon, it took just 1.0145
U.S. dollars to buy one euro, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
The currency received another blow when data published in
Germany confirmed the weakness of the country's economy. Inflation
was virtually down to zero in June, while industrial output in May
fell 2 percent from a year before, according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
"Inflation is still low which means the economy is still in
relative standstill," BankBoston currency strategist Jeffrey
Woodruff was quoted by BBC as saying.
</P>
<P>
The European finance ministers are reportedly discussing what
to do about the euro's fall.
</P>
<P>
When the euro was launched in January, its exchange rate had
been set at 1.16675 U.S. dollars. Since then it has lost more than
13 percent of its value against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Many traders predict that it is now only a matter of time
before the euro and the dollar trade on parity, a move that could
seriously undermine market confidence in the European currency.
</P>
<P>
However, the euro is not the only currency suffering. The Swiss
Franc is at an eight-year low against the dollar, while the UK
pound is hovering at a 35-month low.
</P>
<P>
One purpose of the ministerial meeting in Brussels is to
coordinate policy statements on economic and monetary matters in
the euro zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
