<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riyadh Calls for Lifting Sanctions on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz on Monday called for lifting the seven-year
international sanctions imposed on Libya over the Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
Libya has responded enough regarding the related United
Nations Security Council resolutions, King Fahd said at a weekly
cabinet session held in the kingdom's western city of Jeddah, the
Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"There is no justification for further delay," he said,
stressing that the Libyan people "should live without any
obstacles."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed an arms and air embargo
against Libya in 1992 after Tripoli refused to turn over two
Libyans, who have long been accused by the U.S. and Britain of
blowing up a Pan Am flight in 1988 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
After years of international mediations, especially from Saudi
Arabia and South Africa, Libya surrendered the two suspects last
April for trial in Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the U.N. suspended the sanctions and promised to
lift them 90 days after U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
verifies that Libya has complied with all relevant requirements.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council welcomed last Friday Libya's commitment
to cooperation in the investigation and promised to lift
sanctions as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
