<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Publishes N. Ireland "Failsafe" Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain Monday unveiled complex
proposals designed to eject the Irish Republican Army's political
wing Sinn Fein out of Northern Ireland's government unless
republican guerrillas give up their arms.
</P>
<P>
A bill described by Prime Minister Tony Blair as a "failsafe
mechanism" said the province's political institutions would be
suspended if any party failed to meet its commitments on
decommissioning weapons, according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
After the suspension, Britain's Northern Ireland secretary
would call two meetings of the suspended assembly in Belfast to
review the situation, the second ending in a vote.
</P>
<P>
Once the Northern Ireland secretary ended the suspension, the
executive's chief minister and his deputy and other ministers
would be able to resume their offices.
</P>
<P>
The complex six-clause bill will be debated by the House of
Commons Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But David Trimble, leader of the main Protestant party, the
Ulster Unionists, said after a 90-minute meeting with Blair
earlier Monday that his party still had problems with it and
planned to table amendments.
</P>
<P>
Blair plans to rush the bill through parliament so that
Northern Ireland's devolved government can be put in place with
full powers transferred from Westminster by Sunday, Reuters said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
