<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statistics Canada Reports Tourism Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Statistics Canada reported a 5.4
percent increase in tourists spending in the first quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Tourists spent 9.4 billion Canadian dollars (6.392 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first three months, 5.4 percent higher than that
of the same period of last year, Statistics Canada said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Non-residents spent 2 billion Canadian dollars (about 1.36
billion U.S. dollars) traveling in Canada, as compared with 7.4
billion (about 5.032 billion U.S. dollars) spent by Canadians on
domestic tourism.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada put the spending increase by foreign visitors
at 12.8 percent, which is more than three times the 3.5 percent
spending rise by Canadians traveling domestically.
</P>
<P>
The spending increase by foreign visitors was attributed to
strengthening currencies in France, Japan and Britain. Increased
travel by Americans was also considered accountable for the rise.
</P>
</TEXT>
