<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's Human Development Index Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- An official with the United Nations
 Development Program (UNDP) said here Monday that Angola's 1999
human development index continues its downward trend this year.
</P>
<P>
Alieu Sallah, UNDP coordinator in Angola, made the remarks at a
ceremony to launch the agency's 1999 human development report.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that of the 174 countries on the list, Angola
ranks 160th, down from the 157th position last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Angola's human development index
falls into the lower category, even among many under-developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, if evaluated against the Southern African Development
 Community members, Angola ranks the 6th owing to its respective
high openness in trade, and its place in oil and diamond export,
second only to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Sallah believed that since the civil war in Angola has ravaged
people's lives, people in the country still have to make great
efforts to rid Angola of humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP report which was launched simultaneously in more than
100 countries Monday also touched on the pros and cons of economic
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Take Internet as an example, Angolans who have access to
Internet only accounts for 0.2 percent of its population, while in
the United States, about 20 percent of its people can now roam on
the information network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
