<HEADLINE> Iran's Foreign Debts Stand at 14.89 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's total foreign debts stood
at 14.89 billion U.S. dollars at the beginning of the current
calendar Iranian year which started on March 21, the evening
newspaper Kayhan reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was about 2.77 billion dollars higher than the
amount of 12.117 billion dollars at the beginning of last Iranian
year, the daily quoted a report from the Central Bank of Iran
(CBI) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The amount of foreign debts to become due this Iranian year
will be 7.599 billion dollars and the figures in coming four
years will stand at 2.437 billion, 1.037 billion, 0.547 billion
and 2.468 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the country needs to pay off 5.63
billion U.S. dollars of its arrears in the current Iranian
calendar year.
</P>
<P>
Iran failed to pay off its due debts of 3.395 billion dollars
in the past Iranian year because its oil incomes dropped by some
3 billion dollars from the budget projection as a result of the
drop in oil prices in the year.
</P>
<P>
Hit by oil price fall during the past year, Iran was seeking
to reschedule the repayment of its foreign debts, mainly with
Italy and Germany.
</P>
<P>
CBI Governor Mohsen Nourbakhsh said in February that Tehran
reached agreements with its trade partners to reschedule 2
billion dollars of its debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
