<HEADLINE> UNDP: Poverty Pervasive in Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- While significant progress has been
made in human development worldwide, poverty continues to be
pervasive in a number of developing countries, according to a
report by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The UNDP global human development report for 1999 launched here
Monday by UNDP resident representative Omoefe Oyaide said that
from 1975 to 1997 life expectancy in developing countries
increased from 53 to 62 years while the under-five mortality fell
from 149 to 84 per 1,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
For the sixth consecutive year, Canada ranks first in the human
 development index followed by Norway, the United States, Japan
and Belgium, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It said Sierra Leone has remained in the last position followed
by Burundi, Burkina Faso, Ethiopia and Niger.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has moved down from 146 to 151 out of the 174 countries
between last year and now. Zambia's slide should not be seen as a
decline in the human development index for the country but may
mean that countries which are worse off have improved at a greater
pace than Zambia, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The index has grown in importance over the years and become an
important barometer of the state of social development and the
human condition globally, it said.
</P>
<P>
Oyaide said globalization is more than the flow of money and
commodities but the growing inter-dependence of the world's people
through shrinking space, time and disappearing of borders.
</P>
<P>
Twenty percent of the world's population who live in the
highest income countries have 86 percent of the world's gross
domestic product (GDP), 82 percent of the world's export market,
68 percent of foreign direct investment and 74 percent of the
telephone lines, she said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, she noted, the bottom 20 percent in the
poorest countries have only about one percent in each category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
