<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets Sudanese Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Monday met with his Sudanese counterpart Omar al-Bashir on the
sidelines of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) summit opened
in Algiers, Algeria, in the day.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Mubarak told Egypt's Middle East News Agency
that the talks were held "within the framework of contacts"
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the ties between the two countries "are continually
improving," while commenting on whether the meeting indicated
progress in removing tension in bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the two leaders is rare since the
Cairo-Khartoum ties soured in 1995 after Egypt accused Sudan of
masterminding an assassination attempt on Mubarak in Addis Ababa,
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also blamed Sudan for sheltering Islamic militants who
have been waging an insurgency since 1992 in an attempted to
topple the secular Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has denied both charges.
</P>
<P>
The ties have been improving steadily in the recent two years
after the two sides repeatedly expressed readiness to end tensions
and exchanged visits by senior officials. It has been reported
that the two sides are considering a visit to Egypt by the
Sudanese president.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Middle East News Agency said on Monday that
Mubarak has sent a message to al-Bashir about his visits to the
United States and France early this month, a further sign of the
warming-up of the relations.
</P>
<P>
After receiving the message delivered by Egyptian Charge
d'Affaires in Khartoum Desouki Fayed, Sudanese First Vice
President Ali Osman Taha expressed gratitude to Mubarak and lauded
his efforts in restoring Arab unity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
