<HEADLINE> First No-Confidence Motion Against New Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- In a sign of strength of the
new government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the coalition faction
in the Knesset (Parliament) Monday easily defeated a no-confidence
motion, the first since Barak took office last week.
</P>
<P>
The no-confidence motion, presented by the largest opposition
bloc Likud, was foiled in a Knesset voting after failing to muster
a majority support. The vote was 31 for, 63 against and five
abstained.
</P>
<P>
The Likud has submitted the motion in protest against Barak's
handling of the coalition negotiations and his intention to expand
the cabinet from 18 ministers to 24.
</P>
<P>
During the 42 days of coalition talks since the May election,
Barak had initially preferred the right-wing Likud, which controls
19 seats in the 120-member Knesset, as a coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
But he abandoned the idea after it became obvious that the
internal struggle in the party and its hard-line policy would
stand in the way of his effort to move forward the stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He has finally managed to form a coalition of 75 seats, the
broadest parliamentary majority in Israel in years.
</P>
<P>
In its first meeting since taking office last Tuesday, the
cabinet of Barak approved almost unanimously Sunday a bill which
will expand itself from the present 18 ministers to 24.
</P>
<P>
Barak initiated the bill in an effort to accommodate the large
coalition in his cabinet, but the Likud said it violates Israel's
basic laws on government.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset began a stormy debate on the bill Sunday after a
Knesset committee in charge of procedures agreed to exempt it from
a 48-hour waiting period required by laws before being presenting
for discussion.
</P>
<P>
The bill is almost assured of approval in a vote scheduled
Tuesday afternoon since all ruling partners have agreed to the
government expansion while signing coalition agreements with
Barak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
