<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Against Gun Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Alliance, an
opposition in South Africa, Monday rejected the government's
proposed new gun law as " short-sighted", saying the draft
legislation would penalize the owners of legally licensed
firearms.
</P>
<P>
"(It) will not contribute one iota toward combating the crime
wave sweeping through South Africa," party spokesman Jan Bosman
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The new law will "render law-abiding citizens defenseless" and
will also open the door for more violent attacks with arms, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The tough draft law, leaked to a weekend newspaper, may require
 applicants to undergo psychometric testing. It effectively
prohibits ownership of firearms for lawful self-defense, outlawing
about 90 percent of all licensed firearms. It proposes a six-month
period for gun owners to declare and hand in their guns.
Thereafter, "harsh and severe" measures should be in place to
prosecute those still in possession of illegal firearms.
</P>
<P>
Bosman said the alliance believed that the new gun laws would
not curb the current violence, murders and crimes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
