<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Spend 187 Mln Dlrs to Fix Y2K Bugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Finance Minister Mikhail
Kasyanov said Monday that Russia will spend an estimated 187
million U.S. dollars to tackle the Y2K problem, almost half of the
originally projected sum of 370 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said priority funding would be given to defense and security
agencies.
</P>
<P>
However, the Defense Ministry will receive only 13 million
dollars for fixing the bug. It will have to seek the additional
10.7 million dollars needed from its own sources, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will receive 6 million dollars while the
State Customs Committee and the Taxation Service Ministry will
have to look for funding on their own.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russia's State Telecommunications
Committee Chairman Alexander Ivanov said Monday that the
preparation of computer networks to withstand the Y2K bug would be
complete in November.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that some agencies do not seem to be aware of the
dangers and that foreign intelligence services may take advantage
of the situation.
</P>
<P>
He called for the establishment of special task forces to
monitor the situation on the night of December 31.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov also called for fewer flights and the halt of certain
hazardous industrial processes and a switch to manual control in
some production and management fields.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are over 140,000 computer systems and
networks in Russian state offices, one fifth of them vitally
important for the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
