<HEADLINE> France Pulls Out Military Advisors From Mauritania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- France has pulled out all its
military advisors from Mauritania, as was demanded by the
Mauritanian government, reported Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted a reliable source in Nouakchott as saying Monday
that all of some 40 French military advisors have left by
different planes by Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 37 Mauritanian military interns studying in
France have also arrived home, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
Mauritania asked France to pull out its military advisors after
a court in Montpellier, southwest France, accused a Mauritanian
intern, Captain Ould Dah, of "crimes of torture" committed in his
own country 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The court's action greatly angered Mauritania, which also
imposed a visa requirement for all French nationals wishing to
visit the country. 
</P>
