<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Calls for Efforts to Narrow Gap Between Knows, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- In the race to lay claim to
knowledge, the global gap between haves and have-nots, between
knows and know-nots, is widening, said the Human Development
Report 1999, released here Monday by the U.N. Development Program
(UNDP).
</P>
<P>
Writing computer programs and revealing genetic codes have
replaced the search for gold, the conquest of land and the command
of machinery as the path to economic power, the 262-page report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Internet, the worldwide computer link-up, is "the
fastest-growing tool of communication ever," with the number of
users expected to grow from 150 million today to more than 700
million in 2001, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Information and communication technology are tremendous tools
for development and can open a fast track to knowledge-based
growth, a track followed by India's software programming,
Ireland's computing services and the Caribbean's data processing,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
But many of those who most need access cannot obtain it. An
invisible barrier has emerged that "true to its name, (it) is like
a world wide web, embracing the connected and silently, almost
imperceptibly, excluding the rest," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the report called for a shift of research towards
the needs of the world, rather than just of those who pay. It
recommended the establishment of a group of independent scientists
to identify technological problems that, if solved, would
contribute to human development, particularly of the world's
poorest people, and to human security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report called for a review of the intellectual
property rights agreement under the World Trade Organization --
first raised in world trade talks in 1986 to crack down on
counterfeit goods, but now involved in the ownership of life
itself.
</P>
<P>
Although trade and intellectual laws, such as patent
legislation, are increasingly determining the path of nations, the
intellectual property rights agreement was negotiated with little
input from many of the developing countries, which are now feeling
its impact, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it was negotiated before most governments and
people understood the social and economic implications of patent
on life, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Patent laws pay little attention to the knowledge of indigenous
people, and on what can be owned: "The result: a silent theft of
centuries of knowledge from developing to developed countries,"
the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Currency Ends Weaker on Offshore Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- South African currency, the
rand, ended weaker against the U.S. dollar Monday, remaining above
the psychological 6.1000 level on offshore dollar demand.
</P>
<P>
The enthusiasm around life insurer Old Mutual's listing failed
to ignite the rand and at 1600 local time (1400 GMT), the currency
was at 6.1150 per dollar from Monday's close of 6.0885.
</P>
<P>
The market was pretty quiet Monday with some dollar demand out
of London and a marginal demand from New York players late Monday
afternoon, market sources said.
</P>
<P>
They said it was probably jobbers looking to make marginal
profit who were active, almost ignoring Old Mutual's listing on
the London and Johannesburg Stock Exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Expectations were that with the listing, there would be rand
demand which would have strengthened the local currency.
</P>
<P>
The local currency opened the session around 6.0950 per dollar
and then firmed slightly to around 6.0750. However the rand's
strength did not last.
</P>
<P>
It soon gave in to offshore dollar demand and weakened to its
intra-day worst level of 6.1310 later in the day. At midday it
was quoted at 6.1125 per dollar level.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said the reluctant participation of offshore
players could be related to dropping interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The South African banks first announced rate cuts last month.
More rate cuts are expected soon as the South African Reserve Bank
is said to prepare a cut by seven basis points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
