<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Study Breast Milk for Toxins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The British government is launching
a study to probe the extent to which breast milk from British
mothers is contaminated with poisonous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The study follows a World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) report
released Monday, which found more than 350 chemicals, from
substances such as perfume, suntan lotion and pesticides, in
Britain's breast milk samples.
</P>
<P>
Although many of these are not dangerous, it said British
infants may be taking in 42 times the safe level of dioxins.
</P>
<P>
And according to the WWF, cow's milk, which is used in infant
milk formulas, could be equally contaminated.
</P>
<P>
These poisonous chemicals can build up in the body over time
and cause cancer, immune system damage and hormonal imbalances,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the British government, believing further research is
needed, is telling mothers in Britain not to panic. Government
experts, the WWF and child health specialists also believed that
the benefits of breastfeeding were far too great to stop.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the safe limits over a lifetime it was not a cause
for concern," said a spokeswoman from the Ministry of Agriculture,
Fisheries and Food.
</P>
<P>
She added that "the total amount that we are talking about fits
quite comfortably into the total amount that somebody is supposed
to get, especially given that environmental exposure to this sort
of thing has been falling over recent years."
</P>
<P>
Government officials announced that a new project is being set
up in northern England, which will recruit about 1,000 mothers
from Yorkshire area to take part in a research project led by
Leeds University.
</P>
<P>
The Leeds survey will attempt to collect a representative
sample of breast milk to form an "archive" of milk samples
reflecting social groups, diets, and number and position of
children in families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
