<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Official Highlights Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Globalization should be an
instrument for greater and faster human development and not
detract from these objectives, Zimbabwean Planning Commissioner
Richard Hove said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hove was speaking during the official launch of the 1999 United
Nations Human Development Report whose theme is "globalization
with a human face".
</P>
<P>
He said globalization had resulted in unprecedented forces and
the digital revolution had worked their way into societies,
business, governments and everyday lives.
</P>
<P>
Technology and globalization should give developing countries
new opportunities for development, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With globalization, the focus is on attracting investors who
would bring into the developing countries technology, capital,
processing know- how and enter into partnerships with domestic
entrepreneurs," he said.
</P>
<P>
To succeed today, said the official, business and government
must understand globalization which meant openness, deregulation
and privatization.
</P>
<P>
The report said 20 percent of the world population living in
the highest income countries controlled 86 percent of the world
gross domestic product, 82 percent of world exports, 68 percent of
direct investments and 74 percent of world telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
Another 20 percent of the world population living in the
poorest countries only had about one percent of the same sectors,
it added.
</P>
<P>
According to Hove, as long as globalization remained dominated
by economic aspects and the spread of markets, human development
would be unavoidably squeezed.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe's development was too slow as a result of the
socio- economic difficulties that the country was going through.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government was working to ensure that the
various macro- economic variables were brought into alignment, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
