<HEADLINE> U.N., Indonesia Work for Secure Ballot in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and
Indonesia have been in close contact to improve security
conditions in East Timor for a ballot to determine the future of
the territory, U.N. officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ian Martin, special representative of U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, met Monday with Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas
on the preparations for the vote to see whether the 800,000 East
Timorese want special autonomy within Indonesia or independence.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place in Dili, East Timor's capital, where the
U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) is based.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMET quoted Alatas as saying that a number of people were
being investigated by the Indonesian authorities for their alleged
involvement in recent incidents in East Timor and action will be
taken to prevent setting illegal roadblocks in the territory.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement reached between Indonesia, Portugal
and the United Nations on May 5, a "popular consultation" will
take place next month in East Timor, a former Portuguese colony
until 1975 but annexed by Indonesia a year later.
</P>
<P>
Recent violent activities reportedly involving pro-integration
and pro-independence militias have led Annan to delay vote
registration by three days until Saturday. He had already put off
the poll by two weeks from the original date of August 8 because
of security concerns.
</P>
<P>
The "requisite certification" of security conditions and the
opening of registration will be confirmed on July 16 if concrete
progress is made on improving the security situation in East
Timor, Annan told the U.N. Security Council over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. spokesman said Monday that the U.N. chief was still
wanting to start registration this week and that Martin would meet
with the Indonesian Task Force Wednesday to assess the progress in
this direction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
