<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq's Fulfilment of Export Quota Depends on Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's fulfillment of the oil
export quota under the sixth phase of the U.N. oil-for-food
program depends on oil prices on the world markets, said an Iraqi
oil official on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Saddam Al-Hassan, executive director of the Oil Marketing
Department in the Oil Ministry, said that Iraq has signed 76
contracts to sell Iraqi cruel oil under the current sixth phase
which started on May 25, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq exported 54.8 million barrels of oil valued
at 750 million U.S. dollars in June. And the average daily oil
export reached 890,000 barrels through southern Iraq's Baker
harbor and 950,000 barrels through Turkey's Mediterranean port of
Cehan.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the oil-for-food program, Iraq has
been allowed to export 5.2 billion dollars worth of oil in every
six months to buy food, medicine and other basic needs for its
nearly 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq was just able to export 3 billion dollars of oil
in the fourth phase and 3.9 billion dollars in the fifth phase
due to the sagging oil prices on world markets and severe lack of
oil spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The oil prices on world markets have climbed to some 16 dollars
per barrel from last year's record-low 10 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iraq signed 1,096 contracts worth 590 million dollars under
the fourth and fifth phases of the program to purchase spare
parts for its oil sector, but few of the contracts have been
implemented, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long complained that the U.S. and British envoys
in the U.N. Sanctions Committee have been blocking the approval
of its contracts signed with foreign companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
