<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland March Passes Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The most important Protestant
parade of the Northern Ireland marching season passed off
peacefully Monday amid tight security as efforts to secure a
political solution in the province continue.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 20,000 members of the Protestant Orange Order, who
believe the province should remain part of the United Kingdom, are
taking to the streets of Belfast for their traditional 12 July
parades.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of troops were on hand to keep the Orangemen and
nationalist residents apart. Police have put barricades to block
off the Ormeau Road area in south Belfast, a mainly nationalist
district which is a likely flashpoint.
</P>
<P>
However, according to reports from Belfast, there was no
incident at the most feared flashpoint, the barring of a local
lodge at Ormeau Bridge.
</P>
<P>
Because of residents' objections, one group of Orangemen were
prevented from marching through Ormeau Road, its traditional
route. Instead, the Parades Commission allowed them to re-route to
join the main Belfast Orange parade.
</P>
<P>
In protest at this decision, up to 20,000 Orangemen from all
over the city were converging on Ormeau Park, which is right
beside the flashpoint area.
</P>
<P>
Robert Saulters, the head of the Orange Order, has called for a
trouble-free day but did not rule out the possibility of trouble
later on as the parade continues.
</P>
<P>
"No matter what is run anywhere, football matches, anything,
there can be violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Monday's march took place at a crucial time in the peace
process of Northern Ireland as the UK Government is due to unveil
legislation designed to break the deadlock in the Northern Ireland
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian People Called to Join Protests Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Political parties in Iran on
Monday called on the people to join university students to
protest a recent unauthorized crackdown on students by the
security forces (police).
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, 15 main political groups from both
moderate and conservative factions called on the people to hold a
gathering at the Tehran University Wednesday afternoon to protest
"the brutal attack on students by a group of willful security
forces," the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that such an act cannot be regarded as a
natural accident rather it should be looked upon as part of
premeditated plan targeting the achievements of the May 23, 1997
presidential elections, in which President Mohammad Khatami won a
landslide victory over the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Thanking President Khatami for defending universities, it
voiced sympathy with the students injured in the incident and
called for arrest of the masterminds and perpetrators of the
bloody incident.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the student Basij, a paramilitary body, of the
Tehran University also announced to hold a gathering in front of
the university on Tuesday "to protest and unveil the invisible and
visible hands" behind the police attack on the university
dormitory complex on Thursday night and Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of continued student protests, clashes erupted
again on Monday noon between students and the police as students
attempted to hold demonstrations outside the Tehran University
campus in defiance of the ban on illegal gatherings by
the Supreme National Security Council (SNSC).
</P>
<P>
Around the Vali-Asr Square in downtown Tehran, a group of
university student demonstrators threw stones and sticks at
policemen as they were trying to disperse and round up students.
</P>
<P>
Several angry demonstrators dragged down two plainclothesmen from
a motorcycle and set fire to it while others chased the policemen
into lanes.
</P>
<P>
Calm returned to the square one hour later, only after the
police used tear gas to disperse the students while police
helicopters hovered overhead around the square.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eyewitnesses said that a shot was fired by a
motorcyclist, who was believed to be a member of the hard-line
Ansar Hezbollah (Friends of the God Party), in another gathering
of over 1,000 students and university staff and professors
gathered at the Tehran University campus.
</P>
<P>
Students believed that Ansar Hezbollah joined hands with the
police to crack down the student rally on Thursday night
protesting the approval of the new press law and the closure of
the leading moderate daily Salam (Hello).
</P>
<P>
Students said that at least seven students were killed by
the police, even if the SNSC announced on Sunday that no student,
but a military officer off-duty, was killed in the crackdown and
all the 200 arrested students have been released.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tabriz University in northwestern Iran on
Monday confirmed that a religious student was shot dead and
several others injured on Sunday during protests in the university.
</P>
<P>
Iranian leaders have expressed concern that the student
protests would be misused by "opportunists" against the Islamic
system.
</P>
<P>
Condemning the police attack as "unacceptable," Iran's Supreme
Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei cautioned that students should watch
out and identify the enemies.
</P>
<P>
Iran's moderate President Khatami also called on students to
cooperate with the government in restoring law and order and
avoiding conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
