<HEADLINE> Norway Grants $7 Million to Tanzania for Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 12 (Xinhua) - The Norwegian government has
granted 54.6 million kronors (about seven million U.S. dollars) to
the Tanzanian government for constructing a power line linking
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
An agreement for building the 122-kilometer-long power line,
between Sumbawanga in southwest Rukwa Region of Tanzania and
Mbala in northeast Zambia, was signed Monday in the Tanzanian
capital Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Signing the agreement, a permanent secretary in Tanzania's
Ministry of Finance, said a new sub-station will be built in
Sumbawanga and a sub- station in Mbala will be expanded. The
66-kilovolt transmission line will be connected with local power
distribution network.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the project is to replace electricity generated
from imported fossil fuel with hydro-electrical power sources in
the Rukwa Region, he said, adding that the project will be
operational within one year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
