<HEADLINE> Lebanese Government Urged to Save Prisoners from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese prisoners' rights group
Monday called Lebanese authorities to make every efforts to save
Lebanese prisoners held in an Israeli jail in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We called on the country's president, prime minister and house
speaker to use their power as much as possible to save Suleiman
Ramadan and his colleagues," said an appeal issued by the National
committee for Lebanese Held in the Israeli Prison of Khiam.
</P>
<P>
"We asked Lebanese government to summon ambassadors in Beirut
of the United Nations Security Council's five permanent member
states to brief them the situation in Khiam prison," the appeal
added.
</P>
<P>
It said scores of Lebanese prisoners at the notorious Khiam
jail suffered severe bruises in a clash with Israeli troops in its
occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis used tear gas canisters, whips and clubs to subdue
the prisoners' mutiny and five mutineers were taken to hospital in
nearby Marjayoun for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Among them is Ramadan, who has only one leg and whose other leg
was amputated after he developed gangrene in Khiam.
</P>
<P>
The clash was reportedly triggered by an attempt by the
prisoners to stage a huger strike to mark the July 14 Day of
Solidarity for Lebanese held in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The committee said that 130 Lebanese are jailed at Khiam
without trial for participation in the resistance movement or
collaborating with Lebanese guerrillas in attacks against Israeli
forces and its ally South Lebanon Army (SLA).
</P>
<P>
The militia has been running the jail under the supervision of
Israel that set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 in a bid to protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting trying to oust
Israeli forces and SLA out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
