<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has agreed to export three tons of vegetable
margarine to Iraq under the U.N. oil-for-food program, the
Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Awni Hashem, director of the Egyptian Trade Center in Baghdad,
was quoted by the English-language newspaper as saying that the
two countries signed an agreement worth 80 million Egyptian pounds
(23.53 million U.S. dollars) in Baghdad on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He added that more contracts would be signed between the two
sides on Egypt's exports of detergents, soap and dairy products to
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's citrus exports to Hong Kong, China, stood at
15.5 million U.S. dollars in the first quarter of this year, the
Al-Akhbar daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The amount was 14.81 million dollars more than that in the
whole of 1998, the newspaper quoted Egyptian Minister of Trade and
Supply Ahmed Gowaili as saying.
</P>
<P>
Citrus export accounts for 79.4 percent of Egypt's total
exports to Hong Kong, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Moroccan Bank for Trade (MBT) estimated the
potential investments in the mobile phone sector in Morocco at
about 4 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign financial institutions such as the U.S. Citi Bank,
the British Barklays, the Dutch Amro and the German Komertz Bank
have expressed willingness to finance the expansion of Morocco's
mobile phone sector, the Al-Hayat daily Monday quoted sources of
the MBT as saying.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Twenty-six projects for potable water and 18 for
sewage disposal will be built in southern Egypt later this year,
the Al-Ahram daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Housing and Urban Communities Mohammed Ibrahim
Soleiman said that the potable water projects have a daily
capacity of 284,000 cubic meters and that of the sewage projects
stands at 259,000 cubic meters a day.
</P>
<P>
Following the government's growing efforts to improve the
infrastructure and public utilities in the cities in Upper Egypt,
179 water projects have recently been opened in addition to 12
sewage treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Saudi economy in 1998 maintained good performance
and registered a real positive growth for the fifth consecutive
year, said a recent report by the Arab Institution for Investment
Protection.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth rate stood at 1.6 percent in 1998, compared
with 2 percent in 1997, the Al-Alam Al-Youm daily Monday quoted
the report as saying
</P>
<P>
It estimated the country's gross national product (GNP) last
year at 66.49 billion riyals (17.73 billion U.S. dollars),
compared to 64.1 billion riyals (17.09 billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 the country's gross domestic product (GDP) hit 488.3
billion riyals (130.2 billion dollars), down by 10.8 percent from
547.4 billion riyals (145.97 billion dollars) in 1997, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Public Business Sector Atef
Mohamed Ebeid said on Sunday that a new company will be set up to
manage, modernize and rehabilitate spinning and textile companies.
</P>
<P>
The new company will include foreign experts in the industry,
representatives of the private sector and public banks, including
the National Bank of Egypt and the Suez Canal Bank.
</P>
<P>
The company is designed to provide a suitable atmosphere to
introduce the privatization process of the selected spinning and
textile companies in a bid to increase their exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
