<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Get Access to Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- African leaders participating in
the on- going 35th summit of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) have been urged to get access to Internet, the so-called
information highway.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by Mark Malloch Brown, administrator with
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), when addressing a
press briefing here Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said Africa's poverty is at least in part attributed to its
general absence of access to advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
"Africa, which accounts for some 10 percent of the world's
population, has only 0.1 percent Internet access rate, the lowest
in the whole world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The hi-technology on the Internet can provide many
opportunities of business for African countries in dire need of
technical guidance, Brown added.
</P>
<P>
African leaders gathered here for the three-day summit of the
continental organization, which started Monday. As many as 46
heads of state and government and 2,400 delegates attended the
opening ceremony of the summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit, the last of this century, is widely regarded as one
of paramount importance to the future of the 53-member bloc and
the whole continent as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
