<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Move Pharaonic Temple due to Ground Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Culture Farouk
Hosni said on Monday that Egypt will relocate a 2,600-year-old
Pharaonic temple to protect it from the rising subterranean water.
</P>
<P>
Hosni told reporters that the Temple of Hibis in al-Kharga
Oasis, 500 kilometers south of Cairo, will be moved to a new site
some 500 meters away.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's leading construction firm, Arab Contractors, will
dismantle all statues, obelisks and columns in the temple, which
covers 1,200 square meters, and put them in place on the new site,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The project is estimated to cost 20 million Egyptian pounds
(5.88 million U.S. dollars) and scheduled to be completed in two
and a half years, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
It will be Egypt's largest project of the kind since the
rock-cut Temple of Ramses II in Abu Simbel near the border with
Sudan was dismantled and reerected under a UNESCO project in 1968
to protect it from flooding by the creation of the Lake Nasser
behind the Aswan High Dam on the Nile.
</P>
<P>
The temple was first built by King Bsmatik II of the 24th
dynasty around 660 B.C. to worship ancient Egypt's chief deity,
Amon. It also hosted statues of Amon's wife, Mut, the goddess
Isis, her husband, Osiris, and their son Horus.
</P>
<P>
The temple was rebuilt in 510-490 B.C. during the reign of
Darius who was the first Persian to occupy Egypt. Persian invaders
maintained Pharaonic deities to appease their conquered subjects
and prevent insurgences.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed el-Saghir, a leading archaeologist of Pharaonic
antiquities, said the temple has been deteriorating because of
rising underground water that was eating away at the foundations.
</P>
<P>
The temple has to be moved to a dry site in time in an effort
protect the antiquities, el-Saghir said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cote d'Ivoire, Tanzania Win OAU Medals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The medals were presented to the two countries for their
efforts in helping African refugees, according to an official with
the committee in charge of the medal.
</P>
<P>
The conditions of this symbolic and significant distinction are
the attribution to African unity and solidarity, and the spirit of
assistance, said the official with the OAU committee who refused
to be identified.
</P>
