<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Calls on D.R.Congo's Rebels to Adopt Truce Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- France urged on Monday the rebel
forces of the Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R.Congo) to adopt
the truce agreement signed last Saturday in Lusaka by six African
states involved in the one-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The truce agreement signed in Lusaka by the leaders of the
countries concerned makes up without dispute an important step
toward a solution of the crisis of the Great Lakes," said the
French Foreign Ministry in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"France calls on the rebellion to join it without delay and on
all sides to respect its application, so that this chance of re-
establishing peace and security and shortening the sufferings of
the people in this region not be missed," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Six Africa countries including Rwanda, D.R.Congo, Uganda,
Angola, Zimbabwe and Chad, which involved in the war in the D.R.
Congo, signed the agreement, but the rebels did not.
</P>
<P>
A leader of the Congolese Rally for Democracy (CRD), one of the
main rebel forces, said on Monday in Kigali, Rwanda, that it is
not bound by the truce.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have not signed the agreement because the leader of
CRD, Emile Ilunga, and the leader of another rebel force the
Movement de Liberation du Congo (MLC), Jean-Pierre Bemba, dispute
over who should be the right one to sign it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
