<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Holds U.S. Embassy Bomb Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Two Egyptians appeared in a British
court Monday on suspicion of involvement in last year's bomb
attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The two suspects, Ibrahim Hussein Adbel Hadi Eidarous, 42, and
Adil Muhammad Abdul al-Majid Bari, 39, were arrested by Scotland
Yard Sunday after receiving extradition warrants from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Their appearance before London's Bow Street Magistrates Court
Monday is believed to be the beginning of a legal process which
the U.S. hopes will lead to the extradition.
</P>
<P>
The Americans have made it clear that they believe the two men
were part of a conspiracy to murder on the attacks over the U.S.
embassies on August 7, 1998, which killed at least 215 people in
Nairobi and 11 in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
U.S. extradition warrants allege that the two Egyptians
conspired with Islamic militant Osama bin Laden to murder American
nationals.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden, a Saudi dissident, is at the top of the FBI's wanted
list. He is believed to be coordinating militant Islamic groups
who have dedicated themselves to waging a holy war against
Americans.
</P>
<P>
Prosecuting lawyer Arvinder Sambei, representing the U.S.
government, said both Eidarous and Bary had handled documents
claiming responsibility for the bombings and that both were found
in possession of false passports.
</P>
<P>
Both men were silent in court but their British lawyers denied
they were involved in the attacks, saying the case is "a cocktail
of surmise and sensationalized hypothesis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
