<HEADLINE> Chinese Aid Materials for Yugoslavia Reach Romanian Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 12 (Xinhua)-- Three batches of Chinese aid
materials, worth of 10 million yuan (1.1 million U.S. dollars),
have reached the Romanian port city of Constanta on the last-leg
of shipment to the Yugoslav capital Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian Red Cross Society (RRCS), which will be
responsible for the railway transport of those goods provided by
its Chinese counterpart, held a grand reception ceremony in
Constanta on Monday, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
While praising both the Chinese and Yugoslav peoples as the
friends of his people, Dumitru Toma, secretary-general of the
Constanta office of the RRCS, promised in the ceremony to quickly
and safely convey this batch of medicine, food and tents to the
destination.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Counselor to Romania Dragan Rkovic thanked China for
providing large amount of medicine to his country. Most Yugoslav
pharmaceutical firms, which were severely damaged by the NATO
bombing, would take time to recover and China's aid at this time
was especially precious, he added.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Chinese Consul-General to Constanta Chen
Guangzhong hoped the Yugoslav people would unite together to
rebuild their country
</P>
<P>
During the NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia, the Chinese Red
Cross Society airlifted a batch of blood products to Yugoslavia
via Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
