<HEADLINE> Over 400,000 Somalis Facing Starvation: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 12 (Xinhua) -- More than one million people in
Somalia are facing serious food shortages, with over 400,000 at
risk of starvation, the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) said in a press release available here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a special report released in Italian capital Rome Monday,
the FAO said the food outlook in Somalia in 1999 is extremely
grim.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. organization attributed the famine condition in the
Horn of Africa country to insufficient rains, unusually hot
weather, the long- lasting civil war and uncontrolled crop pests
and diseases.
</P>
<P>
The rain season starting last April has largely failed, the FAO
said, adding that intensified fighting between different factions
has aggravated the situation.
</P>
<P>
Factional fighting and insecurity have not only curtailed
commercial and economic activities, but also forced large numbers
of people to move in search for food and safety, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Malnutrition is reported to high and increasing. The already
precarious food supply situation is expected to worsen in the
coming months with renewed fighting in some areas and more
population displacement.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that some 70,000 people have been displaced by
food shortages and insecurity, the FAO said in its report.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. organization has estimated that the total emergency
food aid requirements stand at 52,000 tons for 1998/99 ending in
July this year.
</P>
<P>
Some one quarter of the requirements has been delivered, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
