<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latvian President Urged to Block Language Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen Latvian public
associations, mostly ethnic Slavs, Monday urged President Vaira
Vike-Freiberga not to sign into law a controversial bill on an
official language passed by parliament last week.
</P>
<P>
The bill, if not revised, would fan the flames of ethnic strife
and would be "dangerous for the state and society," the groups
said in an appeal published in Riga, the Latvian capital.
</P>
<P>
The signatories of the appeal included the Russian Community of
Latvia, the Baltic-Slav Society, the Human Rights Committee, the
War Veterans' Organization of Latvia, the Ukrainian Union of
Latvia, the Promen Belarussian Society and the Armenian Society of
Latvia, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Latvian parliament Thursday passed a bill mandating the use
of the Latvian language at most public functions and in business,
even those involving only Russian speakers, who account for 40
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
Russia reacted immediately after the draft law was passed,
condemning it as "openly discriminatory" and complaining to the
Council of Europe and the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Council of Europe Secretary-General Daniel Tarschys said the
draft law failed to comply with Latvia's international
commitments, while the European Commission warned that the
proposed law might prevent the European Union from starting
accession talks with Latvia.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Latvia's New Party also urged President
Vike-Freiberga not to endorse the controversial draft law and
asked her to return the draft to parliament for reconsideration,
</P>
<P>
"The New Party maintains that the law passed is imperfect,
clearly politicized and fails to meet the interests of Latvian
society or the strategic interests of the country," the party said
in an appeal.
</P>
<P>
Vike-Freiberga plans intensive talks with various parties until
Thursday, after which she will make up her mind, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The New Party, which came up with a case against the planned
law when parliament was still debating it, had particularly strong
objections to a provision that would ban the use of any language
other than Latvian at public events.
</P>
<P>
The party also had fears about proposed language restrictions
for private business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
