<HEADLINE> Algerian President Presses for Continental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika said here Monday afternoon that ravaging conflicts
would exert in-depth implications on society and therefore called
for stability and security in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered after he was elected chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) at the opening ceremony of the
35th OAU summit, he said the impact of persistent conflicts on
inter-African relations and particularly on the fate of thousands
of displaced people is politically unacceptable and morally
unbearable.
</P>
<P>
"This is unacceptable because such a situation does not emanate
from fatality," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In truth, this problem of conflicts, because of its acuteness
and persistence, refers basically to the problem of collective
security in Africa," Bouteflika added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that attention should be focused on the
strengthening of a set of doctrines capable of harmonizing the
concepts, at the African level and in relation with the United
Nations as the main organ responsible for peacekeeping and
security in the world.
</P>
<P>
A genuine policy of conflict prevention and overall recovery of
the continent depends greatly on the pursuit and intensification
of efforts for economic development and integration at the
regional and continental levels, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Burteflika was elected President of Algeria in April this year
and will take up a one-year rotating chairmanship of Africa's
biggest organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
