<HEADLINE> Kashmir Issue Effectively Internationalized: Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Monday the Kashmir freedom fighters' successes in
Kargil along the Line of Control and Pakistan's diplomatic
initiative have effectively internationalized the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation over radio and television Monday night,
Sharif said that the Mujahideen (freedom fighters)'s capture of
Kargil along the Line of Control (LoC) was basically to draw the
world's attention to the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that the appeal by the Pakistani government to
the Mujahideen to disengage from the Kargil heights is not a
defeat.
</P>
<P>
The Mujahideen had a complete success in their mission, Sharif
said, adding that "they gave practical form to our stand that
Kashmir is a nuclear flash point."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kashmir movement would continue and would meet
its logical conclusion of freedom. "The Kashmir movement will
continue with more vigor, and Kargil is a significant pause in the
struggle for Kashmir," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Mujahideen by vacating the heights have produced an
opportunity to resolve the Kashmir issue bilaterally with the
interest and pressure of world powers," said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, had given diplomacy another chance despite
India's "belligerent and aggressive action" along the Line of
Control in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"Our diplomacy was not based on rashness, and our initiative
was not taken under any pressure or confusion," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the latest visit to Pakistan by U.S. General
Anthony Zinni, Sharif said Pakistan made it clear to the United
States that Kargil was not an isolated episode, it was part of the
larger Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
On his visit to the United States last week, Sharif said the
U.S. government saw reason in Pakistan's stand. U.S. President
Bill Clinton admitted that Kashmir was the main issue affecting
peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the Kashmir issue is resolved, South Asia will continue
to face the danger of war," said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the joint statement issued after his talks with
Clinton, Sharif said that with normalcy at the LoC, Pakistan and
India would start bilateral talks on all outstanding issues
including the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
Sharif noted that Clinton also assured to take "personal
interest" in resolving the Kashmir issue. "This assurance was
unprecedented," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
