<HEADLINE> German FM, Greek leaders Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer held talks here Monday with Greek leaders on the Balkan
reconstruction, relations between the European Union (EU) and
Turkey as well as Greek-Turkish ties, and the latest developments
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who arrived here Monday for a visit, met with Greek
Prime Minister Costas Simitis, Parliament President Apostolos
Kaklamanis and his Greek counterpart, George Papandreou.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the talks, Fischer stressed that Thessaloniki,
the largest city in northern Greece, must be the seat of the
agency for the reconstruction of the Balkans. The decision made by
the EU leaders in Rio de Janeiro must be respected because the EU
believes that Greece could play a significant role in the
reconstruction of the Balkans, he said.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders decided in late June to base its agency for the
Balkan reconstruction in the northern Greek port city of
Thessaloniki, but certain European countries are now trying to
move the agency to Pristina, capital of the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo. Greece has expressed its hope that the EU will not change
its decision, and said that it will respond in a convincing manner
to those opposed to the choice of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
The German minister praised Greece for its effective
contribution to the positive conclusion of the crisis in Kosovo
and its constructive role in the stability pact reached for the
region.
</P>
<P>
As for the EU's ties with Turkey, Fischer said that Turkey must
get closer to the EU by making significant steps of progress in
the sector of human rights.
</P>
<P>
There could be no such rapprochement for as long as the death
penalty is implemented in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the relations between Greece and Turkey, Fischer hailed the
initiative for the talks between Papandreou and his Turkish
counterpart, Ismail Cem, in New York, saying that it gave hope for
the future in their bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He also backed Cyprus' efforts to join the EU, and said that
the island's steady course toward its accession into the EU must
continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
