<HEADLINE> Chung Asks for Half Berth from South America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 12 (Xinhua) -- FIFA vice president Chung Mong-joon
said Monday the "best way" to solve the conflict between his world
soccer governing body and the Asian Football Confederation (AFC)
was that South America gives up half a berth for the 2002 World
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Chung, also chairman of the South Korea Football Association,
said that "there is no other way" to get back AFC into the world
premier soccer competition unless South America, who has ten
members in South American Football Confederation, gave up half a
berth.
</P>
<P>
This was a unanimous conclusion reached by the 43 members in
AFC, who had 4.5 berths for the finals after European soccer body
UEFA offered half a berth, Chung added.
</P>
<P>
Chung said he had informed FIFA of the AFC position, warning
that AFC may not take part in the World Cup draw slated for
December in Japan if FIFA rejects the proposal. 
</P>
