<HEADLINE> Belgrade Demands Respect for Sovereignty, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia Monday urged the
U.N. mission (UNMIK) and international peacekeepers (KFOR) in
Kosovo, the Serbian province, to fully respect the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
This aims to create a safe environment for the multi-ethnic
society and set up an interim transitional administration in
Kosovo under relevant Security Council resolution, it said.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Yugoslav
Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic said, "I should like to
underscore once gain the important need for KOFR and UNMIK, in the
performance of their mandates, fully to abide by the principle of
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
He also called upon the U.N.-sanctions military and civilian
units in Kosovo to show "respect for, and the unity of, the legal,
economic and monetary institutions of the Republic of Serbia and
those of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also denounced a "document" signed in
Pristina, provincial capital of Kosovo, on July 2, "under the
auspices of UNMIK and KFOR."
</P>
<P>
The "document" was singed by Bishop Artemije and Momcilo
Trajkovic, and by one of the leaders of "the Kosova Liberation
Army," the separatist and terrorist organization, Hashim Tachi,
Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
The "Joint Statement" was signed by the alleged
"representatives fo the Serbian people" who "were really not
elected, and therefore they do not enjoy legitimacy, and cannot
either represent or make undertakings on behalf of anyone but
themselves," said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
"United Nations representatives in Kosovo and Metohija do not
have the powers to choose or proclaim arbitrarily Serb or other
representatives of any national community, and to promote them as
participant of the political process," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Providing sponsorship for these and similar activities by the
United Nations mission (UNMIK, KFOR) is therefore in contravention
of the letter and spirit of Security Council Resolution 1244
(1999), and it represents an attempt to manipulate the sentiments
and interests of Serbs in the province of Kosovo," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the foreign minister asked Annan to take steps,
according to relevant Security Council resolutions, to ensure the
full compliance with the Security Council resolution, especially
with regard to guarantee of a safe environment and full protection
of citizens and their property, and an end to terrorist acts such
as daily murders and kidnapping of civilians, burning of homes and
entire villages, destruction of Serbian medieval monasteries and
cultural sites.
</P>
<P>
He also demanded respect for the laws and principles of the
State governed by the rule of law by everyone, in accordance with
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
