<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Troops to Withdraw Soon From DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The withdrawal of Zimbabwean troops
from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is expected to start
within the next three to four months, following the signing of a
ceasefire agreement signaling the end of the 11-month war in that
country.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Defense Minister Moven Mahachi told the Zimbabwe
News Agency here Monday that the peacekeeping forces from the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the United Nations (UN)
would have been deployed to the DRC by November this year.
</P>
<P>
Ideally, he said they wanted at least 30,000 peacekeeping
troops deployed to enforce any truce and police the peacekeeping
process. But Zimbabwe would not be sending any troops for the
peacekeeping process.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, our troops will be coming home. The ceasefire agreement
entails a period of three to four months. We think that within
the next three to four months they will be able to come home. The
reason for allowing this period is that we can not leave a
vacuum," Mahachi said.
</P>
<P>
However, Mahachi could not specify how many Zimbabwean soldiers
were deployed in the DRC for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
"We have never wanted to disclose but when the actual
withdrawal starts, we will reveal the figures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, together with Chad, Namibia and Angola, deployed
troops to the DRC when Tutsi rebels backed by Uganda and Rwanda
launched an attack on DRC President Laurent Kabila's forces in
August last year.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi said his ministry was in the process of submitting
names of missing persons who might have been captured to the
International Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed in Zambian capital Lusaka Saturday
evening, hostages should be released by Wednesday, and OAU
observers were expected on the ground within 15 days from the
signing and exchange of prisoners of war to take place within 30
days.
</P>
<P>
Asked how effective the agreement was without the signatures of
the rebels, Mahachi said all the rebels had accepted the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
"The delay does not mean that they disagree with the ceasefire
agreement.
</P>
<P>
It was a problem of who should sign. We are not hoping for the
worst," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
