<HEADLINE> 616 Zimbabwean Families to Be Resettled by August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will have
 resettled 616 families on prime agricultural land by the end of
August this year, as the country continues its land reform
program, a top government official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Msika, national chairman of the Land Reform and
Resettlement Committee, told the country's senior news editors at
a press briefing that 15 farms measuring 27,841 hectares had been
acquired this year for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
Resettlement will take place on a total of 54,000 hectares of
land on 23 farms acquired by the government this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the first phase of the program, 71,000 families were
resettled on 3.4 million hectares. Under the current second
phase, the government intends to acquire five million hectares of
land for resettlement over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Msika invited editors from all sections of the media for a
frank talk on Zimbabwe's controversial land acquisition and
resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
He asked the editors to be patriotic, and ensure that their
reporters report positively on the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
