<HEADLINE> Portuguese-Speaking Countries Attend Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The parliaments of the Community of
 Portuguese-Speaking Countries opened its second forum here Monday
 with all seven speakers advocating the establishment of a
communication network to enhance ties among them.
</P>
<P>
Almeida Santos, speaker of Portuguese parliament and executive
chairman of the forum, said at the opening ceremony that the
parliaments of the Portuguese-speaking countries should not only
strengthen exchanges in information and experience among
themselves, but also expand relations with parliaments of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the parliaments of the community, which groups
Mozambique, Angola, Cape Verde, Guinea Bissau, Sao tome &AMP;
Principe, Portugal and Brazil, should take advantage of new
technologies to reinforce their democratic systems.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting aims to exchange information and
experiences among parliaments of member states and discuss
parliament's role in future democratic system.
</P>
<P>
One of the other major goal of the forum is to discuss the
challenges facing the parliaments in the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament Forum of the Community of Portuguese-Speaking
Countries was established in Portugal in 1998. On the same year,
the forum held its first meeting in Lisbon, capital of Portugal.
</P>
</TEXT>
