<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Islamic Militants Go on Trial in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court on Monday began
the trial on 14 terrorist suspects, including three minors, for
the killing of policemen and Egypt's Coptic Christians.
</P>
<P>
The hearing in the State Security Court in Cairo was procedural
and the court adjourned the trial until October 11 for further
preparations, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They are charged with killing nine policemen and Coptic
Christians, robbing banks and jewelry shops in four southern
governorates in 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
Their secondary charges include membership in an outlawed
insurgency group and sheltering extremists. The news agency did
not specify the name of the group.
</P>
<P>
Egypt usually slaps harsh punishment on Islamic militants. If
convicted, the defendants will face a maximum penalty of death.
</P>
<P>
The minors, who are aged between 15 to 17, will face a maximum
of 15 years' imprisonment, if convicted. They would serve their
first year in a juvenile correction facility until they become of
age.
</P>
<P>
Muslim extremists launched an insurrection in 1992 in an
attempt to overthrow Egypt's secular government and replace it
with strict Islamic rule. At least 1,200 people, mainly policemen
and Islamic militants, have died in the campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
