<HEADLINE> Tanzania Willing to Join UN Peacekeeping Force in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Foreign Minister
Jakaya Kikwete said here Monday that his country will be ready to
take part in the United Nations peacekeeping force in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) if asked to do so.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete, who has just returned from DRC peace talks in Lusaka,
Zambia, told a press conference that the UN peacekeeping force
will be arriving in DRC in six months, and a team of observers
consisted of the UN and the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
personnel will be formed.
</P>
<P>
He said the negotiation team in Lusaka resolved that Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba, who is the mediator of the DRC peace
talks, should go to Boma and Kisangani in the vast central African
nation on his return from the on-going OAU summit in Algiers,
Algeria, to get the two rebel leaders to be represented by a
single signatory.
</P>
<P>
On refugees, Kikwete said arrangements will be made to
facilitate their return to their homeland except those who have
valid reasons for continued stay.
</P>
<P>
Six African countries involved in the DRC conflicts signed a
peace deal in Lusaka Saturday to end their confrontation since DRC
rebels took up arms

against President Laurent Kabila last August.
</P>
<P>
However, the rebels have not inked the agreement as leaders of
two factions, Emile Ilunga of the Congolese Liberation Movement,
and Congolese Rally for Democracy's Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, have
both claimed the right to sign for the rebel side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
