<HEADLINE> Gore Announces Anti-crime Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
Monday proposed photo licenses for all new handgun owners while
announcing a broad anti-crime agenda.
</P>
<P>
Crime had dropped across the nation since President Clinton's
anti-crime bill was passed, but those measures were only the
beginning, Gore said in a speech at the Boston Police Department.
</P>
<P>
Gore, the Democratic presidential front-runner, proposed
tougher penalties for those who commit crimes in front of
children, for repeat drug abusers and for those who commit hate
crimes, calling on Congress to pass the Hate Crimes Prevention
Act.
</P>
<P>
School shootings this year in Colorado and Georgia, have turned
gun control into a major issue in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
"I will insist on a policy of zero tolerance toward guns and
drugs in our schools," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cheap, easily concealed handguns, known as "junk guns" or
"Saturday night specials," would be banned under his proposal.
</P>
<P>
Gore said if he was elected as president he would oppose any
effort to loosen federal restrictions on concealed weapon and
fight any attempt to give the gun makers special legal protection.
</P>
<P>
"I make this pledge today," Gore said. "If the people of this
country entrust me with the presidency, I will fight to protect
American families by launching the most effective and
comprehensive anti-crime strategy our nation has ever seen."
</P>
<P>
Gore said earlier that he supports raising the age for handgun
possession from 18 to 21; barring juveniles from possessing
assault weapons or large-capacity ammunition clips; imposing new
penalties for adults who sell guns to minors; and requiring safety
locks on guns.
</P>
<P>
As vice president, Gore cast the tie-breaking vote in the
Senate earlier this year in favor of a bill that would have
required a three-day check period for purchase of a gun at a gun
show and safety locks on firearms. The measure was ultimately
defeated in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Gore's anti-crime package also includes a "Stay Clean to Stay
Out" policy that says defendants in drug-related crimes who are
awaiting trial must get off drugs to stay out of jail.
</P>
<P>
He suggested increasing use of computers in law enforcement,
investing in software that community police could use to map and
target high-crime areas.
</P>
<P>
Other features of the anti-crime package include establishment
of "gang-free zones," more aid for professional development and
retraining of police officers and increased spending on
after-school programs for youths and anti-drug efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
