<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Clashes erupted again between Iranian university
students and anti-riot police Monday noon in the wake of protests
against the recent police crackdown on students.
</P>
<P>
Around the Vali-Asr Square in downtown Tehran, a group of
demonstrating university students threw stones and sticks at
policemen who were trying to disperse them.
</P>
<P>
Several angry demonstrators dragged down two plainclothes
policemen from a motorcycle and set fire to the vehicle while
others chased the policemen into lanes. (BC-Iran-Students-Clashes)
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- An officer of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army
(SLA) was wounded in south Lebanon on Monday, the Voice of the
People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Shibli, 50, was moderately wounded in a roadside bomb
explosion when his car was travelling in his village of Aita Shab
in the western sector of the border zone in south Lebanon under
Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
There has been no group claiming responsibility for the bombing
blast, which is always used by guerrillas of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, for attacks on the militia and Israeli
forces. (BC-Lebanon-Millitiaman-Wounded)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A training plane crashed on Sunday, killing two and
injuring another, the evening newspaper Resalat reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The plane TB-200 with three people aboard crashed around 09:30
hours local times (0500 GMT) near a lake, east of Damavand, Tehran
province, the report said. (BC-Iran-Plane-Crash)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In a sign of strength of the new government of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the coalition faction in the Knesset
(Parliament) Monday easily defeated a no-confidence motion, the
first since Barak took office last week.
</P>
<P>
The no-confidence motion, presented by the largest opposition
bloc Likud, was foiled in a Knesset voting after failing to muster
a majority support. The vote was 31 for, 63 against and five
abstained.
</P>
<P>
The Likud has submitted the motion in protest against Barak's
handling of the coalition negotiations and his intention to expand
the cabinet from 18 ministers to 24. (BC-Israel-Vote)  
</P>
</TEXT>
