<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Urged to Sign Cease-Fire Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Monday urged rebel leaders in the Democratic Republic
of Congo to sign the cease-fire agreement as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Council members "strongly" urged them to resolve differences
and sign the pact, council president Malaysia's Agam Hasmy said in
a press statement after the council met on the matter.
</P>
<P>
While expressing their dismay at the rebel leaders' move, the
15 council members emphasized that earnest efforts to find a
peaceful solution to the conflict in D.R. Congo "should not be
held hostage to the internal division among the rebels".
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, they called upon the Governments of Rwanda and
Uganda and other governments who have influence, to make all the
necessary effort so that the rebel movements sign this agreement
and also for the rebel movements to abide by the cease-fire
pending their signature of the agreement," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of D.R. Congo, Namibia, Rwanda, Uganda, Zimbabwe and
the defense minister of Angola signed the agreement in Lusaka,
Zambia on Saturday, capping two weeks of hectic negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The six countries were involved in the one-year conflict in
D.R. Congo.
</P>
<P>
But rebel leaders did not sign the document as they disputed
over who should be the right one to sign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
