<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Quicken Privatization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has set a
December deadline for the completion of the first phase of its
privatization program, Vice-President Abubakar Atiku said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The phase would affect government-owned companies involved in
banking, cement production and oil, Atiku told a meeting of the
30-member presidential consultative committee on the
rehabilitation of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"We would carry out the privatization without compromising
transparency," the vice-president said of the exercise which was
suspended by the former military government after allegations that
it was an opportunity to reward military officers and their
cronies.
</P>
<P>
He also said President Olusegun Obasanjo has set performance
targets for ministers, which focus on "institutional reforms and
policy areas", to evaluate them.
</P>
<P>
Atiku urged members of the committee to devise "ways to restore
the country's economy," which is grappling with an external debt
burden estimated at 30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The ultimate test is how much empirical improvement we can
bring to the quality of life of the citizenry," he said of the
government whose campaign promise was to "make Nigeria great
again".
</P>
<P>
In another development, the vice-president announced Monday
that the country would set up a joint commission with South Africa
to coordinate economic transactions between them.
</P>
<P>
Atiku told a four-member South African delegation that
preliminary discussion on the commission was held with his South
African counterpart Jacob Zuma during the recent Southern African
Economic Summit.
</P>
<P>
He told the visiting delegation that Nigeria would invest in
the steel, telecommunications and gas sectors.
</P>
<P>
"Increased economic collaboration between both countries would
be to our mutual benefit," Atiku said.
</P>
<P>
"Our commitment to privatization should provide an opportunity
for South African companies to invest in our economy," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
