<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Development Report 1999 Launched in 100 World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Human Development
Report 1999 is being launched Monday in Algiers, Beijing, London,
New York and 100 other world capitals.
</P>
<P>
The 10th in an annual series prepared by an independent team of
experts commissioned by the U.N. Development Program (UNDP), this
year's report is on the theme "Globalization with a Human Face."
</P>
<P>
The report argued that the benefits of globalization are not
shared equitably. For instance, 85 percent of the foreign direct
investment in developing and transition countries in the 1990s
went to only 20 countries and industrialized countries hold 97
percent of all patents worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The report also found that the largest single export industry
in the United States is not aircraft or automobiles, but
entertainment, which grossed more than 30 billion U.S. dollars for
Hollywood in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, globalization can enrich the lives of
people everywhere, but only when rules and institutions exist for
stronger, more representative governance that allows for
opportunities to be captured more equitably.
</P>
<P>
Every year since 1990, the UNDP has commissioned the Human
Report by an independent team of experts to explore major issues
of global concern.
</P>
<P>
The report looks beyond per capita incomes as a measure of
human progress by also assessing it against such factors as
average life expectancy, literacy and overall well-being. It
argues that human development is ultimately "a process of
enlarging people's choices."
</P>
<P>
This year's report focuses on the positive and negative aspects
of globalization. It argues that while many millions of people are
being further marginalized by their lack of access to new
technologies, including the Internet, growing inequalities are not
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
The report recommends, among other things, stronger social
policies and actions to buffer the effects of today's "bust and
boom" economy. It urges policy-makers to balance their concern for
profits with concern for people disenfranchised by the turmoil of
the global marketplace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
