<HEADLINE> Year 2000 Proposed as Year of Peace for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The year 2000 was proposed here
Monday afternoon by Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo as the
Year of Peace and Security in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the three-day 35th summit
of the Organization of African Unity, Obasanjo said: "I see the
beginning of a new dawn of hope and prosperity for Africa."
</P>
<P>
The goal for the peace year, Obasanjo said, is to see an Africa
that is at peace with itself and is able to compete on equal
footing with other regions in an "increasingly globalizing and
borderless world."
</P>
<P>
The need for security and stability is a prerequisite for
development and progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo expressed his gratitude to those who worked to achieve
the recently-concluded peace agreements on Sierra Leone and on the
Democratic Republic of Congo, where armed conflicts have brought
Africa under world attention for war and instability.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreements, he said, are a result of their tireless
efforts and staunch belief in the priceless advantage of peace in
places where the citizens can look forward to a life free of
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said that with the completion of the process of
decolonization, Africans have the historic opportunity to forge
the future of their continent in terms of economic and social
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
