<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three U.S. Hospital Deaths Tied to Respiratory Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A hot-water tank at Harford
Memorial Hospital in Maryland State of the United States is the
likely cause of an outbreak of Legionnaires' disease that has
killed three elderly patients and sickened two others, said
reports reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The latest fatality was a patient in the hospital June 18-28,
before health officials discovered the bacteria there, the reports
quoted hospital spokesman Robert Netherland as saying.
</P>
<P>
The man, whose name was not released, was readmitted to the
hospital last Friday and died that evening. Test results came back
last Saturday confirming he had the bacteria that causes
Legionnaires' disease.
</P>
<P>
Another unidentified patient died June 26, and Elizabeth M.
Cox, 79, died last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials believe a hot water tank at the hospital was the
probable source of the bacteria. Water samples taken from the tank
and pipes tested positive for the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Health officials said last Friday that additional cases were
possible because the incubation period for the disease is two to
10 days.
</P>
<P>
The hospital has been calling more than 400 recent patients to
ask them about symptoms and offer free testing if needed.
</P>
<P>
Legionnaires' is a form of pneumonia caused by a common
bacteria often found in air conditioning cooling towers, water
tanks, whirlpool spas and humidifiers. The disease takes its name
from a deadly outbreak at the Pennsylvania American Legion
convention held in Philadelphia in July 1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
