<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Leader Says "Unhappy" over U.S. restriction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard expressed unhappiness on Monday to U.S. President Bill
Clinton over U.S. restriction of lamb imports from this Ocean
country.
</P>
<P>
Howard held a one-to-one meeting with Clinton at the White
House, mainly discussing the issue of Washington limiting lamb
imports from Australia.
</P>
<P>
"I made it plain to him (Clinton) that that issue caused a
greater adverse reaction in Australia on a trade matter than any
other trade issue that I could remember," Howard told reporters
after his talks with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The United States on Wednesday took steps to limit lamb
imports and imposed tariffs after U.S. ranchers complained that
surging shipments of Australian and New Zealand lamb were
driving them out of business.
</P>
<P>
The White House said in a statement that lamb imports will be
limited to the amount bought in 1998, or 31,851 metric tons, and
will be subject to a 9 percent tariff for the first year. The
measures will be enforced from July 22.
</P>
<P>
Both Australia and New Zealand, whose farmers produce about
95 percent of all lamb imported by the United States, have
strongly objected to any import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the Australians "are very unhappy; very, very
unhappy."
</P>
<P>
"We made it very plain that the thing that particularly upset
us was the imposition of a tariff on the in-quota area," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Howard, who is here on a working visit, said he had told
Clinton that Australia would "pursue our remedies in the World
Trade Organization."
</P>
<P>
Howard came to Washington to discuss issues on security,
economy and trade between the two countries, but Australia's
anger over lamb import limit put a damper on the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
