<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Seeks Extension of EU Trade Concessions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Trade officials from the
14-nation Southern African Development Community (SADC) Monday
called for the European Union (EU) trade concessions for the
region to be extended by another 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The trade officials are holding a two-day meeting in Botswanan
capital Gaborone to make preparations for a meeting of trade
ministers on a free trade agreement in the region, Agence France
Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
"The member states seek a waiver from the WTO (World Trade
 Organization) on the current trade arrangement to be continued
for  another 10 years," SADC Chief Economist Chingu Mwila was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"But the EU says the trade preferences could only be continued
for another five years," Mwila said.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason why the SADC member states want a 10-year
waiver is that they still want to restructure their economies
before any reciprocal arrangement could be entered into," he said.
</P>
<P>
The concessions were granted in terms of the Lome Convention's
provisions granted to African, Caribbean and Pacific countries,
due to expire next year.
</P>
<P>
"The fear is that regional industries across the board would
not compete favorably with those from EU," Mwila said.
</P>
<P>
He said the recommendation will be taken to the ministerial
meeting scheduled for Gaborone Wednesday. It will also be
presented to the WTO ministerial conference to be held in the
United States next year.
</P>
<P>
SADC trade officials are also expected to debate a free trade
agreement among countries in the southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted diplomatic sources as saying at the weekend that
member states agreed on the main principles of trade
liberalization, but officials were yet to reach consensus on
"finer details".
</P>
<P>
South African Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin last week
told a regional meeting of the World Economic Forum that the talks
were "well down the track."
</P>
<P>
Erwin said some aspects of an agreement could be implemented by
the beginning of the year 2000, but warned that the road ahead was
fraught with difficulty, given the growing trade imbalances that
exist between the 14 SADC states.
</P>
<P>
Inter-trade between SADC nations has risen from six percent to
20 percent since the democratization of South Africa in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that when parts of the protocol come into effect
early next year it will rise up to 35 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
