<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urged to Do More to Isolate Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A group advocating closer
U.S.-Afghan relations on Monday urged President Bill Clinton take
more actions to isolate Afghanistan's Taliban movement besides
economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Afghanistan Foundation said this should include reaching
out to political moderates of the country and establishing a
special U.S. envoy for the central Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
"It would be good if the president would take the lead on
this," said former House Representative Don Ritter, chairman of
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton last week issued an executive order imposing sanctions
on the Taliban movement for its protection to Saudi-born Osama bin
Laden who is alleged to be behind the bombing of two U.S.
embassies in Africa last August.
</P>
<P>
Ritter told a news conference that the sanctions, though
important, was mostly symbolic as the trade between U.S. and
Afghanistan last year was a relatively small $24 million.
</P>
<P>
He said the Clinton administration should do more to bring
international pressure to "weaken and transform the Taliban."
</P>
<P>
"If the administration does not, it would be appropriate for
Congress to take look at this," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban "must hand over or at very least expel"
bin Laden so that he could stand trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
