<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide System Management Software Market Climbing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Revenues in the worldwide
system management software market are steadily climbing, expecting
to reach 11.3 billion U.S. dollars this year, according to a
report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, they rose 16 percent to 9.7 billion dollars, and by
2003, they will top 18 billion dollars, said the new report from
U.S. market research firm International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
The need to keep business-critical applications running at peak
efficiency and with high availability is driving demand for a wide
variety of system management tools, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
System management software manages computer systems in an
enterprise. Depending on an organizational philosophy, system
management may include network management or be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
According to IDC, U.S. vendors are benefiting the most from
this market's upswing. In 1998, their revenue growth was three
times larger than non-U.S. vendors'. U.S. companies increased
their revenues almost 18 percent to 8.7 billion dollars in 1998.
International vendors, on the other hand, increased their revenues
by less than six percent to 1.1 billion dollars. As a result, U.S.
companies accounted for a dominating 89 percent of the overall
market worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Storage management was the largest segment of the overall
system management software market with revenues of 2.67 billion,
reflecting the importance of data protection on all platforms.
Performance management was the second-largest segment with 2.28
billion dollars. The fastest-growing segment, however, will be
change and configuration management, earning a compound annual
growth rate of 22 percent from 1998 to 2003, IDC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
