<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Criticizes Turkey for Statement on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday criticized
neighboring Turkey for a statement made by Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit concerning the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that Ecevit's statements on Cyprus
constituted an unprecedented provocation to the international
community.
</P>
<P>
With his statements, the Turkish premier placed Turkey outside
the framework of international legality, he said, adding that his
claims ultimately achieved the exact opposite from the intended
result, confirming the provocative and aggressive character which,
in violation of any concept of law, characterized Turkey's policy.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish premier reportedly said Sunday that the Cyprus
problem ceased existing after the creation of the Turkish Cypriot
state and the entire world had to understand the reality of an
independent Turkish state on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north in 1974 when
Turkish troops landed on the island in the wake of a failed coup
seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriots proclaimed a breakaway Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus, which has been recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored talks between the two sides of the island
have failed to make any progress in finding an overall and lasting
solution to the division of Cyprus or toward reuniting it under a
federal system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
