<HEADLINE> UNDP Project Develops Blood Salvage Device </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations
Development Program (UNDP)-supported project has developed a blood
transfusion device which can be used easily in medical emergencies
in developing countries, UNDP reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new device called "EAT-SET" and invented by Nigerian
medical researcher Oviemo Ovadie allows for rapid recovery and
safe reinfusion of blood for patients with internal bleeding, the
organization said in its latest weekly UNDPFLASH.
</P>
<P>
The device, which can be operated manually and in rural ares
without sufficient electricity supply, offers developing countries
a low-cost alternative to expensive high-tech equipment used by
hospitals in the industrialized world, the weekly said.
</P>
<P>
UNDP said it helped the inventor acquire a patent and
intellectual property rights to the device which is already used
in several Nigerian Hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
