<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Settle Dispute on Steel Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the United States
reached a comprise Tuesday on the two countries' long-running
dispute over steel trade.
</P>
<P>
According to Russian Trade Minister Mikhail Fradkov, the two
sides signed two agreements earlier Tuesday, one suspending U.S.
anti-dumping investigations against Russian exporters of hot-
rolled steel, and the other setting quotas on Russian steel
exports to the United States during a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
In what Fradkov described as a compromise following lengthy
and complicated talks, the U.S. agreed to increase delivery quotas
by 30-40 percent as compared with the initial proposal.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Fradkov said, restrictions have been lifted on
Russian wire and instrument-quality steel and quotas raised for
stainless steel exports.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreements provide for regular consultations on
the possible revision of these decisions and that the next
consultations on Russian steel export terms will be held in
Washington at the end of July in the framework of talks between
Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and U.S. Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, Russia would be able to export 2.3
million tons of hot-rolled steel in 2000-2003 and 1.7 million tons
of cold-rolled steel in 1999-2003, worth a total of 1.2 billion U.
S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exports of Russian zinc-plated steel will decrease
by 40,000 tons from the 1998 level, pig iron by 200,000 tons, hot-
and cold-rolled rods by 100,000 tons. The decreased export would
cost Russian producers 250 million dollars in five years.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said, failure to reach a comprise could
cost Russia 1.5 billion dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin
meanwhile acknowledged that the package of Russian-U.S. agreements
do not fully meet Russian interests.
</P>
<P>
The agreement package "does not fully meet the interests of
the Russian metallurgical industry and contains several very tough
provisions for Russia."
</P>
<P>
"The recent problems with Russian exports to the U.S. have
largely been caused by the fact that under U.S. legislation Russia
does not have the status of a country with a market economy," the
Interfax news agency quoted Rakhmanin as saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Moscow would "consistently and firmly work
for such a status, resolutely raising the question in our contacts
with Americans, including high level contacts."  
</P>
</TEXT>
