<HEADLINE> Russia Voices Concern Over Latvian Language Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia expressed "serious concern"
Tuesday on a language bill passed by the Latvian parliament last
week, saying it "would force minorities to assimilate rather than
integrate into society."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said the bill,
which cleared the Latvian parliament last Thursday, "fully ignores
all the proposals of lawmakers from national minorities,
disregards many recommendations" from the OSCE High Commissioner
for National Minorities Max van der Stoel, and strips the
languages of that country's ethnic minorities of "any legal status.
"
</P>
<P>
The bill mandates the use of the Latvian language at most
public functions and in business, even those involving only
Russian speakers, who account for 40 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
The enactment of the bill with such wording would "force
minorities to assimilate rather than integrate into society,
strain relations between ethnic groups in Latvia, deal a tangible
blow to the improvement of Russian-Latvian relations, and throw a
challenge to the international community," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Baltic country's leadership to "display state
wisdom and use its constitutional right" and return the bill to
parliament for revision.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, protests against the language law continued Tuesday
in Riga, the Latvian capital, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
About 100 people, with their mouth tied up with black bands,
were protesting outside the Presidential Palace, holding signs
such as "Language Dictatorship Leads to Kosovo," and "Integration -
Yes, Assimilation - No," Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The protests came after an appeal Monday from 19 Latvian
public organizations, representing primarily Slavic nations, to
President Vaira Vike-Friberg to veto the legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
