<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Sets Preconditions for Dialogue With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- India indicated Tuesday that
resumption of dialogue with Pakistan could be considered only
after Islamabad took three "essential steps" including complete
withdrawal of intruders in Kargil by July 16 morning and putting
an end to sponsoring cross-border terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on the fresh offer of dialogue made by
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Monday night, an External
Affairs Ministry spokesman said, "Our future dealings with
Pakistan will be governed by the sequence of steps already spelt
out."
</P>
<P>
He said that the first essential step was a "total clearing up"
of remnants of "armed intrusion and aggression."
</P>
<P>
"Till this is not completed to our satisfaction," he continued,
"no other steps will be taken."
</P>
<P>
After complete withdrawal, he said Pakistan would have to
reaffirm the inviolability and sanctity of the line of control
(LoC).
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he indicated, would have to abandon encouraging and
abetting terrorism and "dismantle the entire network set up in
Pakistan territory for the purpose."
</P>
<P>
Maintaining that India's commitment to the Lahore process and
the composite dialogue remained, he said New Delhi "would like to
renew the dialogue process and expects that Pakistan will take the
needed steps for that to become possible."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indian troops Tuesday inched towards the line of
control, overrunning the strategic Bajrang post, as operations
continued to flush our remaining Pakistani infiltrators in Kaksar,
Batalik and Drass sectors.
</P>
<P>
In the last 24 hours there was no artillery fire in Mukoh
valley and Kaksar areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
