<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.N. Report Sheds More Light on Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Globalization, a dominant
force in the 21st century's last decade, is shaping a new era of
interaction among nations, economies and people, for better or for
worse.
</P>
<P>
A new report on human development, commissioned Monday by the
U.N. Development Program (UNDP), dwelled on the pros and cons of
globalization, characterized by the current "shrinking space,
shrinking time and disappearing borders."
</P>
<P>
More than 1.5 trillion U.S. dollars are now exchanged in the
world's currency markets each day, and nearly a fifth of the goods
and services produced each year are traded. However, globalization
is more than the flow of money and commodities.
</P>
<P>
While increasing interdependence among peoples and nations
worldwide, globalization is compounding the gap between rich and
poor nations and intensifying the Western dominance of the world's
economic and cultural markets.
</P>
<P>
Opening many opportunities for millions of people around the
world, globalization is creating new threats to human security --
in both rich and poor countries. In the globalization world of
shrinking space, shrinking time and disappearing borders, people
are confronting new threats to human security -- sudden and
hurtful disruptions in the pattern of daily life.
</P>
<P>
For example, globalization creates financial volatility and
economic insecurity, job and income insecurity, health and
cultural insecurity, personal and environmental insecurity, and
political instability.
</P>
<P>
However, poor countries are being growingly marginalized in the
process of globalization, which demands technological advancement
and quality governance. The report warned that the glaring,
growing inequalities in the distribution of wealth pose a
"dangerous polarization" between rich and poor countries.
</P>
<P>
Globalization, as it has been allowed to proceed so far, has
also been driving a deeper wedge between rich and poor countries,
and among people within countries. People in 85 countries are in
fact worse off in many respects than they were a decade ago. In
short, the world fails to share the benefit of globalization
equitably.
</P>
<P>
The 262-page report, the 10th such program since 1990,
concluded that the so-called "rules of globalization" should be
rewritten to save the 60 countries that are worse off than they
were in 1980 from falling even further behind.
</P>
<P>
The report recommended faster debt relief, redirection of aid
to the poorest countries and a task force to review "global
governance." It also endorsed a tax of one American cent on
lengthy E-mails to raise 70 billion U.S. dollars a year that could
be used to connect the world's people who cannot afford to pay the
access to Internet, the world's computing link-up.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report urged a new vision for national and
international policymaking to balance concern for profits with
concern for people disenfranchised by the turmoil of today's
global market.
</P>
<P>
The report called for comprehensive approaches to global
threats to human security such as HIV/AIDS, international crime,
human rights abuses by multinational corporations and transborder
pollution such as acid rain.
</P>
<P>
The report called upon the world community to support the
development of technologies for the poor and build a more
representative and coherent system of global governance, to buffer
the effects of a "boom and bust" economy and address the needs of
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is to put human concerns at the center of the
globalization debate, to end the polarization between the
connected and unconnected, to focus on the global interdependence
of people and not just of financial flows -- to make globalization
work for people, not just for profits," Dr. Richard Jolly,
principal coordinator of the report, explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
