<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lion's Share of Rebuilding Kosovo Fund Unclear At G7 Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Group of Seven (G7) finance
ministers and world financial representatives failed Tuesday to
find who will pay the lion's share of the international aid for
Kosovo reconstruction after a meeting here on a strategy for
rebuilding the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, entitled "High Level Steering Group on Economic
Reconstruction in the Balkans", will also focus on the evaluation
of economic consequences of the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
German Finance Minister Hans Eichel said that Europe would not
bear the rebuilding costs on its own in return for the United
States' having paid for the lion's share.
</P>
<P>
But he said the U.S. and Japan had agreed to pay part of the
aid bill for reviving Balkans economies affected by the war.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, World Bank President James Wolfensohn declared that
G7 countries agreed to supply only humanitarian aid to Yugoslavia,
but look for ways to support Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
"It was recognized that no assistance would be provided to the
former Republic of Yugoslavia other than humanitarian aid, which
would address the most urgent and essential human needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I think the issue in Kosovo is not just money...it's
reconstruction of the morale and spirit of people that have been
brutalized," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the U.S. Secretary Lawrence Summers said
Washington would favor sending economic aid to Montenegro,
reiterating that Serbia would not receive a penny in aid as long
as President Slobodan Milosevic remained in power.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the European Union is talking of putting up about
510 million U.S. dollars for the Balkans reconstruction, while the
World Bank has said that it will commit 60 million U.S. dollars to
Kosovo at the this stage.
</P>
<P>
EU Officials confirmed that western governments and
international agencies were increasingly hopeful that the Kosovo
aid bill would be smaller than they originally estimated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
