<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 1600, July 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The powerful Indonesian Muslim Intellectuals
Association (ICMI) does not back up any presidential candidate,
including incumbent President B.J. Habibie, ICMI General Secretary
Adi Sasono said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"ICMI did not give support to any candidate. There was also not
back-up statement," Adi said, referring to the ICMI's two-day
congress in Bandung, capital of West Java, last week. (Indonesia-
Presidential Candidate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Since the rebels in Congo (K) did not sign on the
cease-fire agreement inked by regional leaders, peace efforts
would continue so as to achieve an everlasting peace in the vast
central African country.
</P>
<P>
Kaire Mbuende, Executive Secretary of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), told reporters here Tuesday
afternoon that after the on- going summit of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), efforts will continue to resolve the
differences that have arisen among rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
The rebel groups, namely the Congolese Rally for Democracy(RCD)
and the Movement for the Liberation of Congo, did not reach
agreement on who should represent all the rebel groups. (OAU-
Congo (K) Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The director of a Jewish cultural center was stabbed
Tuesday by a youth in the building of the main synagogue in
central Moscow, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Leopold Kaimonovsky, 52, was listed in serious condition with
numerous stab wounds. The attacker was seized by visitors to the
synagogue and handed over to the police.
</P>
<P>
The chief rabbi of Moscow, Adolf Shayevich, blamed the incident
on the authorities' failure to crack down on anti-Semitic
declarations. (Russia-Synagogue)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French President Jacques Chirac said on Tuesday that
France offers its entire support to the peace efforts by Britain
and Ireland in Northern Ireland and called on all the parties in
the British province to accept the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
The new plan proposed on July 2 by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern "helps move forward
reconciliation, renouncement of force and disarmament at the same
time," said Chirac in a published statement. (France-N.Ireland)
</P>
</TEXT>
