<HEADLINE> Ulster Unionists Table Amendments to N.Irish Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Ulster Unionists and the opposition
Conservatives Tuesday tabled several amendments to the Northern
Ireland arms and devolution bill being rushed through the British
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The bill, to be debated later Tuesday before the House of
Commons, provides for a suspension of all institutions set up
under the Good Friday Agreement and a wholesale review if
decommissioning does not occur.
</P>
<P>
But Ulster Unionists and Conservatives said they are still
unhappy about the guarantees being offered about what will happen
if the Irish Republican Army fails to disarm.
</P>
<P>
What it lacks, the unionists argue, is a definite timetable for
the destruction of weapons stockpiles to take place and the
certainty the IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, will be expelled
from the executive unless arms disposal starts on time.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, who is also Northern
Ireland's first minister, is proposing the IRA be given four weeks
from the establishment of the executive to begin decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives also want an end to the early release of
paramilitary prisoners if the IRA fails to disarm, Conservative
leader William Hague has told the BBC.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair, who has chosen a high-risk strategy
to get the executive in place by the weekend, Tuesday met John
Hume and Seamus Mallon, leaders of the moderate nationalist Social
Democratic and Labor Party (SDLP), ahead of the debate.
</P>
<P>
Blair wants the SDLP to help Trimble by making clear that they
would be prepared to continue in government without Sinn Fein
should it be excluded from the executive.
</P>
<P>
Dr Marjorie Mowlam, the Northern Ireland secretary, earlier
promised to study the amendments being tabled, but she also gave a
strong hint the government would force the bill through the
Commons using its parliamentary majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
