<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Speeds Talks Over Space Launch From Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin Tuesday dispatched his deputy, Igor Klebanov, to Astana
to negotiate with Kazakhstan to seek permission to launch a cargo
ship from the Baikonur cosmodrome to the Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
The trip was arranged following a telephone conversation
earlier Tuesday between Stepashin and Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev, the government information department said.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov has the mission of conducting talks to settle the
entire range of problems related to the operation of Baikonur, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan suspended all launches from Baikonur in the wake of
last Tuesday's crash of a Russian booster rocket, which could have
unpredictable ecological consequences for the Central Asian
republic because 66 tons of fuel with toxic components was sprayed
over its territory.
</P>
<P>
Space officials warned that Russia's 136-ton Mir space station
may spin out of control and crash down to Earth if Kazakhstan does
not permit a cargo ship carrying critical supplies to blast off
from Baikonur by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Russia still plans to launch the Progress M-42 cargo craft from
the cosmodrome Wednesday to deliver control equipment that would
allow the station to be operated from the ground if its main
computer breaks down.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan has so far remained unwilling to lift the ban on all
Baikonur launches that it imposed after a Proton rocket crashed
into the Kazakh steppe on July 5.
</P>
<P>
"We will not lift the ban until at least preliminary results of
the Proton crash investigation are available," Nurlan Usimbayev,
deputy head of the Kazakhstan Aerospace Agency, said.
</P>
<P>
These results are expected only sometime next week, The Moscow
Times quoted officials as saying at the Khrunichev plant, the
makers of the Proton rocket.
</P>
<P>
If not carried out by Sunday, the launch of the Progress ship
would have to be postponed for another month, said Yury Koptev,
general director of the Russian Aviation and Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
This delay would leave Mir's three-man crew with too little
time to install and test the control equipment before they are
scheduled to leave the station on August 23, Koptev said.
</P>
<P>
"We are now trying to make our Kazakh colleagues understand
that the lack of such a launch will lead us to a situation where
it is equally possible that fragments (of Mir) will fall onto
heads in Kazakhstan and Russia... or any other country within the
range of 51 degrees of latitude," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
