<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Approves 6.67B Dollars of Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,008
manufacturing projects involving 25.35 billion Malaysian rupiah
(6.67 billion U.S. dollars) in foreign investment had been
approved from July 1997 until last May, the Malaysian House of
Representatives was told during question time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The capital inflow was for electrical, petroleum, chemical,
metal and textile industries, Deputy Minister of International
Trade and Industry Kerk Choo Ting said.
</P>
<P>
Johor received 6.6 billion rupiah (1.74 billion dollars) of the
funding followed by Pulau Pinang (6.2 billion rupiah or 1.63
billion dollars)), Terengganu (2.73 billion rupiah or 718 million
dollars), Pahang (2.66 billion rupiah or 700 million dollars),
Selangor (2.56 billion rupiah or 673 million dollars) and Negeri
Sembilan (1.26 billion rupiah or 331 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
He also told the House that since the imposition of selective
capital controls on September 1 last year, the manufacturing
sector received 12.2 billion rupiah (3.21 billion dollars) in
foreign funds as of last May.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, 5.71 billion rupiah (1.5 billion dollars) or
46.8 percent went to the electronics and electrical sectors.
</P>
<P>
On trade missions, Kerk said Malaysia would send eight such
missions to the United States, Japan, Belgium, Germany, China,
Britain and Australia this year.
</P>
<P>
To another question, Kerk said the economic turmoil had not
affected foreign investors' confidence in Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
