<HEADLINE> Iran Blasts U.S. for Interference in Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Tuesday blasted the United
States for "interference" in its internal affairs as Iranian
students continued their protests against police crackdown on
students.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry Spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said that
the remarks by some U.S. officials on the recent Iranian police
crackdown on students are examples of their interference in Iran's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Iran will never allow foreigners to exploit the internal issues
of Iran for political objectives, the Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA) quoted the spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iran, as an independent and free state, will uphold the rule of
law concerning the current events in Iran and will act with
transparency and according to law, said Asefi.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's remarks came after a U.S. official said on
Monday that the recent student protests in Iran reflect an
intensifying struggle of those who support the moderate President
Mohammad Khatami for the future of the Iranian politics.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. State Department spokesman on Monday also called on
Iran to respect the international norm concerning protests and
demonstrations, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on Monday warned
the students that the "enemies" were behind the police assault on
the Tehran University dormitory on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
Condemning the unauthorized police assault as "unacceptable,"
Khamenei called on the students to "watch and identify the evil
hands of the enemies."
</P>
<P>
Following Khamenei's speech, Iran's conservative-dominated
police tightened their control on the streets leading to the
Tehran University where students gathered in the past five days to
protest the police crackdown on a student rally protesting the new
press law and the closure of the leading moderate daily Salam
(Hello).
</P>
<P>
Clashes were reported on Tuesday as thousands of students
intended to stage demonstrations in the Tehran University in
defiance of the ban on any illegal gatherings.
</P>
<P>
IRNA confirmed that clashes occurred between anti-riot police
and a group of "rioters who attempted to create tensions."
</P>
<P>
The police, armed with shields and batons, used tear gas to
disperse the "rioters who are believed to be backed by terrorist
groups and tried to create clashes with police," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The police also blocked the streets leading to Tehran
University and a police helicopter was hovering overhead
broadcasting government announcements on loudspeakers that any
assembly or demonstration was unauthorized.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said that plainclothes policemen shot into the
air as street battles erupted between students and
policemen. Policemen fired tear gas to disperse students and
students hurled stones and clubs back.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tehran main bazaar closed on Tuesday, the first
time in the six days of student protests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
