<HEADLINE> Vietnam Hands over MIA Remains to U.S.A. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam Tuesday returned to the
United States six sets of remains of American servicemen listed as
missing in action (MIAs) during the Vietnam war, Vietnam's
official news agency VNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The remains, recovered in Vietnam-U.S. joint operations during
the 55th joint field activity held from May 4 to June 5, and
collected unilaterally by the Vietnamese side, were examined in
Hanoi by Vietnamese and U.S. forensic specialists.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Vietnam Peter Peterson, representatives of
the U.S. Joint Task Force Full Accounting (JTF-FA) and the Vietnam
Office Seeking Missing Persons (VNOSMP) witnessed the hand-over
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
This is the 74th time Vietnam returned to the United States
remains of American servicemen since 1973. Vietnam has totally
returned to the U.S.A. 748 sets of remains of American MIAs
during the Vietnam war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
