<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Continue to Attack Govt Forces: DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- President Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) said Tuesday that rebels
fighting to oust him are continuing attacking his government and
allied positions despite a peace agreement signed in Zambian
capital Lusaka last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"They (rebels) are still attacking us," Kabila told the
Zimbabwe News Agency after his meeting with Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe in Algiers where they are attending the on-going
35th summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
"They attacked Belenge this morning and yesterday Kabinda," the
DRC president said, without giving details on casualties.
</P>
<P>
He noted that nothing on the ground had changed since the
signing of the Lusaka peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries
together with Rwanda and Uganda signed the peace agreement to end
the 11-month conflict which has pitted at least six African
countries against each other.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said it was still early to judge whether the rebels
would adhere to the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the allied forces including Zimbabwean,
Angolan and Namibian troops, which are fighting on the side of
Kabila against the rebels allegedly backed by Rwanda and Uganda,
would continue to be vigilant as the other parties might violate
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We are watching very carefully on the development taking
place," Mugabe said. "When you go into an agreement at the nature
we signed, you do not doubt the commitment if the other parties,
but you have to remain vigilant as one side might violate it."
</P>
<P>
To ensure that no violations were made, the OAU leaders and
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan would discuss the
modalities of sending observers and peace-keepers to the DRC, said
the Zimbabwean president.
</P>
<P>
According to Mugabe, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba who is
 mediating on the ending of the conflict said that he would go to
Goma and Bukavu in Rwanda on a mission to ensure that the rebels
sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The rebels did not sign the agreement in Lusaka because of a
split in the main rebel movement, the Rally for Congolese
Democracy (RDC).
</P>
<P>
"The rebels have no strength to fight on their own," Mugabe
said. "If they refuse to sign the agreement and continue to
fight, then we will know that their master, Rwanda is still aiding
them."
</P>
<P>
He added that Rwanda's commitment to the honoring of the
agreement would be judged on whether the rebels sign the peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior Rwandan army commander said on condition of
 anonymity Tuesday that rebels in the DRC could fight on to take
capital Kinshasa even if foreign powers involved in the war pulled
out.
</P>
<P>
But Tanzanian Foreign Minister Jakaya Mrisho Kikwete said that
without outside help the rebels would be a spent force and their
campaign to wrest control of the vast central African country from
Kabila would fizzle out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
