<HEADLINE> Pakistan Averts Dangerous War in South Asia: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Tuesday once again defended his latest efforts to defuse
the situation in Kargil, describing it as one of the "courageous
and farsighted steps" to avert a dangerous war in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Sharif made this remark while addressing the parliament members
of the ruling Muslim League and its allies at the Prime Minister's
House, in a bid to take the parliamentarians into confidence on
his recent visit to the United States where he agreed to persuade
the Mujahideen to vacate the positions they occupied in Kargil.
</P>
<P>
He categorically stated that the measures to de-escalate the
situation taken by the government were not due to any weakness but
in the larger interest of peace and progress of the peoples of
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said the steps will open the way for solution of the Kashmir
problem as "now the international community, including the United
States, are involved in it".
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. President Bill Clinton has committed to taking
personal interest in the Kashmir issue. China and Islamic
countries also expressed concern over the situation along the Line
of Control and assured their support to Pakistan, added Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said after the positive response of the
Mujahideen to Pakistan's appeal to withdraw from Kargil, the ball
is in India's court to address the root cause of tension, the
Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
He urged India to resume dialogue with Pakistan as soon as
possible because there is "no other better way" than dialogue for
solution to outstanding issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
