<HEADLINE> Kashmiri Groups Rule out Withdrawal From Kargil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Jehad Council (UJC),
an alliance of 15 Kashmiri freedom fighter groups, Tuesday ruled
out withdrawal from Kargil under any international agreement or
appeal.
</P>
<P>
The organization, after an emergency meeting here, announced to
re-adjust their positions in the Kargil sector as part of their
"new strategy".
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Monday said the Mujahideen (freedom fighters) have
started "disengagement" in several areas in Kargil in the light of
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's appeal to de-escalate the tension
between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, in his televised address to the nation Monday, thanked
the Mujahideen for positively responding to his appeal for
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The Mujahideen are determined to continue their struggle with
full vigor and strength, according to a statement issued after the
UJC meeting.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Mujahideen have changed their positions
in Kargil and chalked out a new strategy for further actions in
the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
