<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Locusts Ravage Crops in Central Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Swarms of locusts have been
spreading across Central Asia, destroying large areas of crops in
Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
In Uzbekistan, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for
Agriculture and Water Resources Bakhtiyer Olimzhonov said Tuesday
that 330,000 hectares of crops have been devoured by the insects.
</P>
<P>
Officials attending a conference on locust control said the
pests had arrived in Uzbekistan from neighboring countries and
that the regions bordering on Kazakhstan are the hardest hit, the
Interfax news agency reported in a dispatch from Tashkent, the
Uzbek capital.
</P>
<P>
In Kazakhstan, locusts have descended upon more than 6.2
million hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
In Russia's Altai republic, which borders Kazakhstan, locusts
have destroyed wide areas of wheat crop and 30,000 out of the
republic's 55,000 hectares of perennial grass, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Lack of funding and hot weather has compounded the situation.
</P>
<P>
In the Siberian region of Novosibirsk, more than 5,000 hectares
of crops were destroyed. In one tragic incident, a villager
committed suicide after seeing all she had sown on here allotment
destroyed, Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
