<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Businessmen Still Show Interest in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Over 1,000 Japanese
businessmen attended seminars on business opportunities in
Malaysia held in conjunction with the Trade and Investment Mission
to Japan from July 7 - 12, proving that the Japanese business
community was still very much interested in doing business with
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"The large presence of the business community reflected the
continuing strong interest of the Japanese to do business with and
invest in Malaysia," said the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry (MITI) in a press release here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
MITI said economic recovery and stability continued to attract
the Japanese business community to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 421 leading businessmen from the Osaka and Kansai
region participated in a seminar on "Business Opportunities in
Malaysia" held on July 12, it said.
</P>
<P>
During the period, more than 102 individual business meetings
were also held between Malaysian delegates and Japanese
businessmen to discuss investment and trade interests.
</P>
<P>
A seminar held in Tokyo on July 8 attracted 704 Japanese
businessmen, MITI said, adding that 172 individual business
meetings were held there.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian delegation comprised 22 representatives from the
state governments of Perlis, Sarawak, Terengganu, Melaka, Pahang
and Johor as well as 32 members from the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The trade and investment mission was headed by Minister of
International Trade and Industry Rafidah Aziz.
</P>
<P>
During these meetings, participants were also informed by the
minister of the progress made in the country's economic revival
and the various measures to be taken to revitalize the economy.
</P>
<P>
Among issues Rafidah addressed at the dialogue sessions
included queries on the ASEAN Free Trade and its implementation
date, promotion of high technology industries in Malaysia and the
local currency's pegging to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Other matters highlighted were issues related to the
acquisition of properties and land by foreigners, investment
restrictions in small and medium industries and visa approvals.
</P>
<P>
In the same statement, MITI said the vice chairman of Osaka
Chamber of Commerce and Industry informed Rafidah that the chamber
will send a 30-member business delegation to Malaysia from August
26 to 28.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will comprise top executives and officials from
the Osaka region and will seek to identify business investment
opportunities here, said MITI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
