<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton and congressional leaders agreed on Monday
night that the government should safeguard Social Security's
future and provide some form of Medicare prescription drug
coverage. But in a White House meeting, they differed on details
and remained especially far apart on the key question of how
deeply to cut taxes amid the nation's booming economy.
</P>
<P>
-- Europe's new single currency, the euro, slid to near parity
against the U.S. dollar Monday. It was the latest tick down in a
relentless, plunge since the euro started trading last December 31.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Federal Government sued Toyota Monday, accusing it
of violating the Clean Air Act by selling 2.2 million automobiles
on which the "check engine" light would not illuminate even when
the vehicles were emitting excessive pollution.
</P>
<P>
-- The most widespread and sustained protests since Iran's
resolution two decades ago spread throughout the country Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Merrill Lynch's President and chief operating officer,
Herbert Allison, quit Monday when it became clear that he wouldn't
become No. 1 at the nation's largest securities firm.
</P>
<P>
-- India silenced most of its guns and called off airstrikes in
Kashmir after Pakistan accepted a Friday deadline for withdrawing
forces from Indian territory.  
</P>
