<HEADLINE> Barak: Progress in Peace Talks May Incur Terrorist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said on Tuesday that progress in the peace negotiations with
the Palestinians may trigger new terrorist attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with senior Israeli military and security
officials, Barak said some extremist groups such as Hamas may be
encouraged by the momentum in the peace process to carry out
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Barak asked all Israeli security agencies to remain alert and
be prepared for countering such possible attacks.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the agencies to increase coordination with the
security forces of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Barak said that in his talks with PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat
and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak over the last few days, he
noted that terrorism might bring the peace process to a halt.
</P>
<P>
The militants of Hamas or Islamic Jihad, who are against
peace talks with Israel, have been behind a series of attacks,
including suicide bombings aimed at scuttling the peace.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office last week, Barak has pledged to make great
efforts to bring peace to the region. And he is also scheduled to
meet Jordan's King Abudullah and U.S. President Bill Clinton later
this week in a bid to push forward the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
