<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly 17,000 Die of Militancy in Kashmir: India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 17,000 people, including
1,416 security personnel, have died of militancy in Kashmir since
1989, according to an Indian government report released here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen top political leaders and 110 other politicians were
also killed while Indian security forces gunned down 7,687
militants in counter-insurgency operations, said the report, which
was submitted to the National Human Rights Commission (NHRC).
</P>
<P>
Of the 16,850 killed in the decade, the central government said
719 were Hindus, 45 Sikhs and 6,219 Muslims.
</P>
<P>
As many as 563 foreign mercenaries were killed by the security
forces while 135 were arrested, the report added.
</P>
<P>
During these turbulence years, 2,491 innocents were abducted,
20 of them being foreigners and 135 women.
</P>
<P>
While 809 of them were released, in most cases after extortion,
torture and exchange of militants, 1,036 were brutally murdered by
the abductor, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The decade-long insurgency also took a high toll on social and
economic development in the disputed area with militants
destroying or burning down 758 educational institutions, 1,264
government buildings, 9 hospitals and 243 bridges.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government admitted that hundreds of thousands of
people, most of whom were Kashmiri pundits, were forced to migrate
out of the valley following attacks and threats by militants and
fundamentalist groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
