<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Economy Improves Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy has improved
slightly helped mainly by a recovery in personal consumption, the
Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said in its monthly report released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EPA revised its assessment upward for the second
consecutive month following a June report in which the agency said
the economy "has stopped declining."
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in 20 months the agency used a phrase to
show an improvement in the economy. The agency last used the
phrase "recovery" in November 1997, and removed the phrase in
December 1997 following collapses of major financial institutions
such as Yamaichi Securities Co. and Hokkaido Takushoku Bank.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in the July report reflects the recent
improvement in corporate confidence, suggesting recovery in
personal consumption and a slight decline in May's unemployment
rate, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency, however, warned if Japan's employment situation
remains severe, it would reduce household incomes, cooling down
consumer confidence again.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the agency expressed a cautious view, saying the
improved assessment does not mean the agency is declaring the
economy has bottomed out or is on a recovery track.
</P>
<P>
They said it is possible that the economy is still only on a
temporary ascent in a general trend of descent.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we are confident the upward trend will continue, the
bottoming out will not be declared," the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
