<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Exports Show Signs of Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Despite a decline of 4.6 percent
in the first half of the year, China's exports showed some signs
of recovery during the period, according to the latest Customs
figures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released today by the General Administration of
Customs show that China's exports reached 83 billion U.S. dollars
between January and June. Imports during the period surged 16.6
percent to 75 billion U.S. dollars, bringing the total trade
volume to 158 billion US dollars, up 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures also show that compared with the corresponding
period last year, exports decreased 7.9 percent in the first
quarter, but only 1.3 percent in the second quarter. The recovery
between the first and second quarters of the year was the first in
21 months, since the Asian financial crisis began in the fall of
1997.
</P>
<P>
Trade experts here noted that the recovery in exports was
mainly due to China's exports to the United States and the
European Union remaining positive. China's exports to the United
States grew 8.4 percent and those to the EU, 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China's exports to the Republic of Korea (ROK),
Japan and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN),
which had been severely hit by the financial crisis, have regained
positive growth. Exports to the ROK in particular have maintained
a double-digit growth rate for four consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
Exports of machinery and electronic products, which account for
the lion's share of China's export volume, rose 9.9 percent to 33.
32 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports of cooking oil, timber, and sawed wood, commodity oil,
pharmaceuticals, rolled steel, paper and paper boards, and
machinery and electronic products have all shown a strong growth
rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
