<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Recruit 10,000 Police Before Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian police authorities are
planning to boost its manpower with the enlistment of about 10,000
recruits into various police colleges before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
No fewer than 2,000 of the 4,000 currently in training are
expected to pass out and join the police force later this year,
the Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But of the groups which make up the 4,000, only less than 500
have been paid salaries since January when police again resumed
recruitment after a four-year break, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Those paid are recruits in group two at the Ikeja Police
College, Lagos, expected to pass out in September along with other
recruits in training at Maiduguri, Kaduna and Orji River, Enugu
police colleges.
</P>
<P>
Police owes these four groups of recruits who were enlisted in
January, April, May and June, five million naira and needs about
the same amount to provide basic facilities and logistics for more
recruits.
</P>
<P>
Inspector-General of Police Musiliu A.K. Smith told commandants
of the four police colleges at the weekend to provide details of
their needs to the authorities before Monday to enable the
Presidency and the Police Affairs Ministry to provide money for
such items before next recruitment.
</P>
<P>
The police also said they would soon begin the recruitment of
drivers as constable into the force.
</P>
<P>
Paddy Ogon, spokesman of the Lagos State Police Command, told
reporters Monday that the Police Force Headquarters has directed
the state command to recruit able-bodied men into the force as
recruit constable drivers.
</P>
<P>
Ogon said that the decision was a result of the determination
of the present administration to strengthen the manpower of
police, to enable it to rise up to the challenges facing the force
in the present civil rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
