<HEADLINE> Quebec Nurses Suspend Strike for 48 Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Striking Quebec nurses suspended
their strike for 48 hours on Tuesday and returned to work in
efforts to negotiate a deal on pay hike with the provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
The 48-hour suspension of the strike, held up for more than two
weeks since June 26, came after the 47,500 nurses voted 93 percent
in favor of a truce decision, which called on both sides to go
back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The Quebec government has accepted the offer and the first
round of talks is expected to be held on Tuesday following the
nurses' demand for an immediate catch-up pay rise of 10 percent
plus another six percent over two years.
</P>
<P>
So far the government's offer has been a five percent over
three years.
</P>
<P>
"The period of negotiations is 48 hours and no more than 48
hours,"the federation of nurses declared Monday.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the government already reached a tentative
agreement with ambulance technicians who were threatening a
general strike on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local reports described the salary of Quebec nurses as the
lowest among their unionized fellows in the country, with their
minimum at 30,340 Canadian dollars (about 20,631 U.S. dollars) and
the maximum at 44,072 (about 29,968 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
