<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Improves in Human Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia ranks 137th out of 174
countries in the U.N. Development Program (UNDP) Human Development
Index for 1999, a slight improvement from last year's ranking of
140th, a local newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP report, which reflects such factors as life
expectancy, education and income, puts Cambodia ahead of Laos,
Pakistan and Nepal, although Cambodia lags behind many Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, life expectancy in Cambodia is 53.4
years, more than 13 years shorter than the world average, the
Cambodia Daily said, while the adult literacy rate is at 66
percent, 12 points below the global average and more than five
points below the average of all developing countries.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, per capita annual income in Cambodia in 1998
was 249 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The human poverty index shows that 70 percent of Cambodia's
population does not have access to safe water and about four out
of 10 persons don't have access to good sanitation. The index also
shows that more than half of Cambodian children younger than five
are underweight.
</P>
<P>
But a UNDP representative in Phnom Penh said that "while many
socio-economic indicators in Cambodia remain low, the report
suggests that a slow but steady improvement in human development
is taking place."
</P>
<P>
"Overall equality in Cambodia is significantly improved,"
Matthew Varghese, UNDP project coordinator added. He also noted
that the poverty rate in Cambodia declined from 39 percent in 1994
to 36 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
UNDP officials suggested investment in education, health and
human resources to help Cambodia improve its ranking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
