<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Strengthen Inter-Africa Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Commerce Minister Mustafa
Bello has assured that his government would give much attention to
intra-Africa trade with a view to strengthening economic
integration in the continent.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with visiting South African Minister of Trade
and Industry Alec Erwin in capital Abuja Monday, Bello said that
the Nigerian government would particularly strive to improve its
economic relations with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Times newspaper Tuesday quoted Bello as saying that
such economic cooperation with South Africa would involve the
establishment of a bilateral trade agreement between the two
nations to provide a legal framework for their entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
It will also involve the establishment of trade offices in both
 countries on reciprocal basis for the purpose of easy access to
the other's market, he said.
</P>
<P>
The South African trade minister described the economies of
both countries as the biggest in the continent, saying that more
business interaction should be encouraged in the continent.
</P>
<P>
"The thinking is that our economies are the biggest in Africa,
but we can't develop Africa by trading with Europe and the United
States alone but by trading within Africa," said Erwin.
</P>
<P>
According to him, South Africa has received a draft trade
agreement from Nigeria but insisted that an investor protection
agreement be entered to safeguard South African business interests
in the most populous African country.
</P>
<P>
Erwin pointed out that investors feel safe when an agreement
protecting their interests is in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
