<HEADLINE> Philippines Creates 300,000 Jobs for Crisis-hit Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
facilitated new jobs for nearly 300,000 Asian financial
crisis-displaced workers in the past year, an official report said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the one-year performance report of the Department
of Labor and Employment (DOLE), the government also put over
34,000 other dislocated ones back on their feet by providing them
with a total of 525 million pesos (13 million U.S. dollars) in
loans.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it gave rice subsidies worth 10 million pesos
(250,000 dollars) combined to 76,923 sugar workers and their
families over the past 12 months, the report added.
</P>
<P>
With more and more factories closing shop and firing workers a
year ago at the height of the Asian crisis, the DOLE was ordered
to intensify its employment-facilitation assistance to job
seekers, especially the newly unemployed ones, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The efforts resulted in the placement of 296,733 job
applicants in new locally available jobs," the DOLE said. "This
somewhat eased the effects of the displacements."
</P>
<P>
The DOLE said it was able to assist this big number of job
seekers over the past year through "stronger networking" of its
regional offices with local-placement centers run by local
government units.
</P>
<P>
As for those who failed to bag new jobs, the government helped
ease the impact of the crisis on 34,267 displaced workers and
their families by extending to them loans through social security
system.
</P>
<P>
A rice subsidy program for sugar workers was likewise
implemented in addition to the cash bonuses and other regular
benefits enjoyed by them.
</P>
</TEXT>
