<HEADLINE> Over 50 Billion Yuan Spent on Food Annually In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Residents of China's largest
metropolis spend more than 50 billion yuan on food annually, a
figure accounting for some 40 percent of all local retail sales.
</P>
<P>
Local expenditures on foodstuffs have been rising for 10 years
as a result of improved local living standards.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, the people of Shanghai prefer to buy food and drinks
at the supermarkets rather than in the small food shops and
groceries that were their usual destinations before the 1990s.
There are now more than 1,000 supermarkets scattered across every
residential neighborhood in the city.
</P>
<P>
There is also a wide variety of food choices now available,
including everything from Chinese-style delicatessen, Western-
style cakes, and health food to fresh fruits and vegetables,
drinks, candies, condiments, canned food, and all kinds of frozen
food.  
</P>
