<HEADLINE> Iranian Police Breaks Up Protest Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative-dominated
police on Tuesday broke up a rally, protesting against police's
crackdown on students, and arrested a number of people, the
Islamic Iranian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, labeled by IRNA as "rioters," threw stones and
clubs at the policemen who were trying to disperse them in front
of the main gate of the Tehran University.
</P>
<P>
But the agency did not say how many protesters took part in the
demonstration and how many of them were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration came after the Tehran University students
announced to end their five-day sit-in at the university campus to
protest the bloody crackdown by the police on university students
on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the students' announcement, "a group of rioters
staged an illegal demonstration in front of the university
Tuesday morning," IRNA said, adding that the same group also
tried to create further tension in several points in Tehran
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The police, armed with shields and batons, used tear gas to
disperse the "rioters who are believed to be backed by terrorist
groups and tried to create clashes with police," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The police also blocked the streets leading to Tehran
University and a police helicopter was hovering overhead
broadcasting government announcements through loudspeakers that
any assembly and demonstration was unauthorized.
</P>
<P>
Following the speech of Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei on Monday, students announced to end their sit-ins and
the student Basijis (military volunteers) also canceled their
rally scheduled to be held Tuesday afternoon in front of Tehran
University.
</P>
<P>
Condemning the unauthorized police assault on students at the
Tehran University dormitory, Khamenei warned that the students
should watch and identify the "evil hands of the enemies."
</P>
<P>
He said that "our main enemies in spying networks are the
designers of the plots" of assaulting Tehran University dormitory
following a student rally protesting the closure of the leading
moderate daily Salam (Hello).
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Propagation Organization (IPO) on Tuesday called
on the Iranian people to hold a rally on Wednesday to support
Khamenei's speech and reiterate loyalty to Khamenei and the
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The IPO said that the enemy's plots aimed at paralyzing the
police, sowing discord among the system's official and
organization and causing disturbances in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
