<HEADLINE> HK Police Strengthen Action Against Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Police have strengthened efforts
to curb drug trafficking activities in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region of China, a police officer said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As part of the strenuous police efforts, officers from the
Narcotics Bureau seized a large quantity of suspected No.4 heroin
and "ice" with a total market value of about 11 million HK dollars
(1.41 million U.S. dollars) during two separate operations mounted
last week and Monday, said Ng Ka-wah, superintendent for
Operations of bureau.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing Tuesday on the efforts made by
Police against drug trafficking activities in Hong Kong, Ng said
that in the first five months this year, Hong Kong Police arrested
a total of 3,674 people for drug-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
"Between January and May this year, 134 kilograms of No.4
heroin were seized while 82 kilograms were seized in the
corresponding period in 1998," he added.
</P>
<P>
The seizure of "ice" in the first five months this year and
last year were 61 kilograms and 62 kilograms respectively.
</P>
<P>
The amount of seized cannabis in the same period dropped
significantly  from 453 kilograms last year to 22.7 kilograms
this year.
</P>
<P>
"The number of 'Ecstasy' seized however increased from 29
tablets between January and May last year to 17,263 tablets in the
same period this year," Ng said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Hong Kong police would continue close
cooperation and regular exchange of information with their
counterparts in China's mainland as well as international law
enforcement agencies to crack down on drug trafficking activities
in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
