<HEADLINE> Singapore to Issue Portrait Currency Notes Featuring First President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 13 (Xinhua)-- As part of its millennium
celebration program, Singapore will issue a new series of portrait
currency notes -the Presidential Notes - in September for general
circulation for the first time in its history, it was announced
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Commissioners of Currency, Singapore, told a press
conference that these notes, the fourth series of currency notes
in Singapore following the series of Orchard, Birds and Ships,
will be launched by Singapore's Finance Minister Richard Hu on
September 9 and there will be a total of seven denominations in
the new series -- 2, 5, 10, 50, 100, 1,000 and 10,000 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Singapore Mint will launch the range of
Presidential Note collectibles and a Currency 21 Exhibition will
be organized in conjunction with the introduction of the portrait
notes, the BCCS added.
</P>
<P>
On front of the design is a portrait of Singapore's first
president, Encik Yusof bin Ishak, who served as head of state when
Singapore achieved self-government on December 3, 1959 and assumed
presidency following Singapore's separation from Malaysia in 1965.
</P>
<P>
On the reverse of the notes are scenes depicting the pillars of
Singapore's success, respectively regarding education, garden
city, sports, arts, youth, government and economics.
</P>
<P>
Noting currency notes with portraits have long been popular in
many parts of the world, a BCCS official told Tuesday's press
conference that the adoption of portrait notes will provide an
opportunity to honor national figures and serve as a unique
anti-counterfeiting feature.
</P>
</TEXT>
