<HEADLINE> Peace Efforts on Congo (K) to Continue: SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Since the rebels in Congo (K) did
not sign on the cease-fire agreement inked by regional leaders,
peace efforts would continue so as to achieve an everlasting peace
in the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
Kaire Mbuende, Executive Secretary of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), told reporters here Tuesday
afternoon that after the on- going summit of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), efforts will continue to resolve the
differences that have arisen among rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
The rebel groups, namely the Congolese Rally for Democracy
(RCD) and the Movement for the Liberation of Congo, did not reach
agreement on who should represent all the rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
This contention on representation results from their grave
differences in strategy and tactics which led to a major split
among the two RCD factions recently.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit on Congo (K), scheduled for June 26, was
postponed several times as ministers were trying to iron out their
key differences on the modalities of cease-fire and deployment of
neutral peace-keeping forces.
</P>
<P>
The war erupted in early August of 1998 and quickly spilt into
a regional war with Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad sending
troops to fight for Congolese President Laurent Kabila while
Uganda and Rwanda backing the rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
Many efforts have been taken trying to restore peace and
ceasing the conflict in the third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
But only the recent summit in Zambian capital Lusaka yielded
results acceptable to all the players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
