<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt's austerity to reshape economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Federal Government
Monday served notice of a painful adjustment process in the
country's endeavor to to reshape its battered economy,.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Tuesday quoted
Vice-President Atiku Abubakar enjoined citizens to gird their
loins for more sacrifice, and indicated that the government is
poised against what he termed the prevailing propensity of many to
make easy money from inflated contracts as well as the lack of
competition in the economy.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the task of reconstructing the economy has
become compelling and demanding that enough be declared the moral
equivalent of war. But the war cannot be successfully prosecuted
by the government alone, but by stake-holders of particularly the
private sector and ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Monday at the State House, Abuja while inaugurating a
22-member Presidential Consultative Committee on the
Revitalization of the Economy, he said: "As a matter of fact, we
foresee a process of painful adjustment for everybody because many
organizations and individuals have become used to making easy
money from inflated contracts, and from the distortions or lack of
competitiveness in the economy."
</P>
<P>
As the new panel, which he heads, settles down to business, he
said it must preoccupy itself with earnestly systematizing,
harmonizing and prioritizing economic policies to ensure their
speedy translation into concrete achievements, measurable either
in quantitative or qualitative terms.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate test, according to the vice-president, is how much
 empirical improvement the government can bring to the quality of
life of the citizenry. "We will not be talking about GDP or GNP,
but the citizen's purchasing power, the reliability of utilities,
access to and cost of his children's education, and his ability to
feed, clothe and house himself," he said.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Abubakar observed that the nation had never
lacked ideas about the nature, ramifications and even the
solutions to her economic problems, pointing out that such ideas
had assumed overflowing dimensions on how to reconstruct the
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
