<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese MacArthur Award Winner Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An official with the Chinese Artists Association said today
that the talented Xu deserves this recognition.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy that he was given the award, a sign that the
latest development in Chinese art has aroused interest in the West,
" the official said on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
He added that this indicates the international community has
gradually accepted Chinese art, and the dialogue between East and
West will continue into the 21st century because of the efforts of
pioneers like Xu.
</P>
<P>
Some media reports said that Xu expresses unique views through
his works.
</P>
<P>
Xu, 44, now resides in New York. He was one of 32 people, and
the only Chinese, granted the award by the John D. and Catherine T.
MacArthur Foundation on June 22.
</P>
<P>
After graduating from China's Central Fine Arts Institute in
the 1980s, Xu became an action artist, creating a number of
controversial works.
</P>
<P>
His best-known works include "A Sealed Book" featuring
unreadable Chinese characters, "Ghost Haunting" with strange
marks on the Great Wall, and "Cultural Animals" depicting sexual
intercourse between animals.
</P>
<P>
Some artists disparage Xu's artistic experiments, while others
appreciate his style.
</P>
<P>
Xu was given the award because he has used traditional Chinese
methods to explore contemporary Chinese arts, according to the New
York-based foundation.
</P>
<P>
There were 1,000 candidates for the award, which is given every
year to the most talented figures in politics, economics, science
and arts. The amount of the award given to Xu was 315,000 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Xu did not know he was a candidate until the names of the
winners were announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Takes Measures Against Portfolio Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Learning its lesson from the Asian
financial crisis, the Philippine government has excluded the
short-term portfolio investments from its computations of net
capital inflows into the country.
</P>
<P>
Edgardo Espiritu, secretary of the Department of Finance, said
Tuesday that instead of being lulled by these "hot" investments,
the government has put in place several reforms that would make
the economy conducive to long-term investments.
</P>
<P>
"Now we are ready for these portfolio investments or what we
call 'hot money.' We no longer include them when we compute our
net inflows," Espiritu told a meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said these "hot money" give economies a false sense of
confidence without considering the need to install measures that
would attract long-term investors.
</P>
<P>
Economists have pointed to the proliferation of these portfolio
investments made by currency speculators in several Asian
countries that led to the financial crisis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
These short-term investors poured their money into robust
economies and immediately pulled them out at the slightest sign of
instability.
</P>
<P>
To attract long-term investments, the Philippine government set
in place several measures to lower the costs of doing business in
the Philippines, including the reduction of mandatory reserve
requirement and overnight borrowing and lending rates.
</P>
<P>
The government has also urged Congress to immediately pass
several economic reform measures such as the General Banking Act,
the Power Sector Reform Bill and the proposed retail trade
liberalization law to encourage more investors to do business in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
