<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Lanka Renames to Seek Int'l Recognition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka on Tuesday renamed its
national carrier Air Lanka as Sri Lankan Airlines to prepare it
for the next millennium as an international airline.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony held here to welcome the arrival of a new Airbus
A340, the first aircraft of the airline with the "Sri Lankan"
logo, Air Lanka Chairman Wickremasinghe unveiled the airline's new
logo, name and colors.
</P>
<P>
To most people in the west, Sri Lanka is still referred to as
the former name "Ceylon". The name "Air Lanka" is not easily
identified with Sri Lanka, said Wickremasinghe.
</P>
<P>
He said the renaming is expected to strengthen the projection
of the country in the international marketplace and the linkage of
the airline as the country's international airline.
</P>
<P>
Wickremasinghe listed other successful Asian examples in the
same vein as Singapore Airlines, Japan Airlines, Malaysia Airlines
and others.
</P>
<P>
Besides the new aircraft obtained today on a dry lease from
Airbus Industries of Europe for five years, Sri Lankan Airlines
will take delivery of six Airbus A330 beginning in October this
year at a cost of some 540 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Wickremasinghe said the airline is also planning to fly to new
destinations in November, including Beirut, Stockholm and Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was also addressed by Minister of Tourism and
Civil Aviation Dharmasiri Senanayake and the airline's director
Gary Chapman.
</P>
<P>
Air Lanka, established in 1979, now flies 26 destinations in 20
countries in Europe, the Middle East, South Asia and the Far East.
Its current fleet consists of four Lockheed Tristar L1011, three
Airbus A340, and two Airbus A320 aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
