<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Accidents Kill 5,000 Yearly in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh incurs a loss of over 10
billion taka (206.2 million U.S. dollars) because of traffic jam
while several thousand lives are lost due to road mishaps a year,
The Daily Star newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Nazmul Hossain, former Bangladesh Road
Transport Authority chairman, at a meeting between the World Bank
(WB) and the Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and
Industries held here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Over 5,000 people were killed in road accidents last year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In Bangladesh, out of 10,000 vehicles, 70 meet fatal accident
while in India and Europe the rate is 35 and 1 to 2 respectively.
Rate of traffic accidents in Bangladesh is one of the highest in
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government and the WB, together with various
stock-holders, had expressed grave concern over the rate of
traffic accidents and fatalities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The WB is now preparing a community road-safety initiative
project for Bangladesh as part of global program against road
accident, according to Jude de Vera, WB's private sector
consultant.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives of the project are to reduce road accidents
as a major cause of death and injury in Bangladesh and also to
improve road-safety in the communities through local community
participation in the design, as well as the implementation of
road-safety programs.
</P>
<P>
The WB consultant appealed to the Bangladeshi business
community for its immediate in involvement with this community
road-safety project with the government and the WB as equal
partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
