<HEADLINE>   Manila Tells Traders to Avoid Currency Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13, (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government Tuesday
asked individuals, financial institutions and currency dealers not
to engage themselves in currency speculation as this will affect
the exchange rate of the Philippine peso against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu told a meeting that some
people speculate in the hope of earning good profits over a short
period when they sense that there are changes in financial policy
developments in the market.
</P>
<P>
The top financial official urged these people to conduct their
businesses fairly and squarely, particularly at a time when the
domestic economy is already on the road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
He said a trader who is able to buy dollars in bulk from
speculators will be forced to sell his notes on the ground that
the dollars in his possession might shed their value, he said.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu also stressed that there is a need to lower further
the present interest rate because the Philippines, among Asian
countries, still commands the highest interest rates and the
country's inflation rate has gone down to a reasonable level.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he discounted claims by former central bank
governor Gabriel Singson that there is danger that some traders
might resort to currency speculations owing to low interest rates
in the market.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he clarified that there are other sources where the
government can resort to such as the remittances of overseas
Filipino workers which already rose by 7 percent in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
He added that the value of exports rose by 30 percent during
the same period, a sign that the country will not run out of its
14- billion-dollar reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
