<HEADLINE> Uganda Moves up in U.N. Development Listing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) said that Uganda has gained more economic and
political development over the past years.
</P>
<P>
UNDP representative to Uganda Daouda Toure made the remarks
when launching the 1999 UNDP Human Development Report in Kampala
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a UNDP report, Uganda is ranked the 158th of the
174 countries, up from 160th last year.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that Uganda is now the 17th poorest country in
the world, up from the 14th poorest last year.
</P>
<P>
Uganda still has potential for improvement if the current
economic and poverty eradication policies are pursued, Toure said,
adding that this east African country still lagged behind compared
to its neighbors like Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Ugandan Minister for the Presidency Ruhakana
Rugunda called for fairer rules in international cooperation and
trade and for the effective participation of the poor countries in
designing such rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Rugunda also reiterated his government's commitment to poverty
eradication.
</P>
<P>
The report titled "Globalization With a Human Face" blames
globalization for the wide disparities between the developed and
the least developed countries.
</P>
<P>
It shows that the rich countries that constitute only 20
percent control 86 percent of the world gross domestic product
while the poorest countries control only one percent.
</P>
<P>
It also shows that the richest countries control 82 percent of
the export of goods and services, 68 percent of foreign direct
investment and have 93.3 percent of Internet users while the
poorest countries have only one percent or less of each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
