<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Inflation at Single Digit Level: C. Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's inflation remained within
the single digit range due to the sustained slowdown in the
expansion of money supply, according to the the Central Bank of
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in its monthly economic review for July
that underlying inflation accelerated in June this year but
remained on the five- percent target set by the bank, the Daily
Nation newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The month-on-month inflation increased to five percent in June
from 2.5 percent and 4.5 percent in April and May respectively.
</P>
<P>
The average annual inflation declined to 6.2 percent in June
from 6.7 percent in May and 7.3 percent in April, the review said.
</P>
<P>
The bank report noted that a policy of restrained monetary
expansion together with the improved availability of basic
foodstuffs, particularly in the first quarter of 1999, led to the
decline in inflation.
</P>
<P>
To maintain low inflation, the central bank said underlying
month-on- month inflation will be confined to within five percent
in the year to June 2000.
</P>
<P>
Inflation within this range would be achieved by ensuring that
money supply expands by no more than 10 percent, the bank added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
