<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Cross-Industry Application Software Market Expands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide sales of business
application software, such as accounting, human resources and
customer service systems that are used across industries are
steadily rising.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released Monday by U.S. market research
firm International Data Corporation (IDC), revenues in the
worldwide cross-industry application market increased 17.6 percent
to 28.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1998. They are expected to
increase 17 percent and exceed 33 billion dollars this year and
reach 66 billion dollars by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Demand for e-commerce functionality is one the many factors
contributing to the growth of cross-industry application software,
IDC said. The increasing popularity of customer relationship
management (CRM) applications is also driving this market
expansion.
</P>
<P>
According to the IDC's 1998 data, Microsoft was the leading
vendor across all application markets, earning almost three
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
CRM applications will become increasingly adopted by companies
of all sizes, said the IDC, adding that faced with growing
competition, businesses currently need to provide better customer
support if they hope to retain their customers.
</P>
<P>
The IDC splits the cross-industry applications market into
accounting, human resources/payroll, materials management, project
management, maintenance management, sales forces automation,
marketing automation, customer support and field service, word
processing, and business performance measurement.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, accounting was the largest segment, earning over six
billion dollars or accounting for 21.5 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
According to the IDC, demand for cross-industry applications is
strongest in the United States, which accounted for just less than
50 percent of worldwide revenues with 13.8 billion dollars. By
2003, the country will account for more than 50 percent with 34.3
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Vowed to Increase Tariffs on EU Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States has vowed to take
firm and swift action to increase tariffs on products from the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky made the remarks
after arbitrators of the World Trade Organization (WTO) ruled here
Monday that the United States lost 116.8 million U.S. dollars per
year because of the continuation of the European Union's import
ban on hormone-treated beef.
</P>
<P>
"The arbitrators' decision today confirms that under WTO rules,
the EU must pay a price for failing to comply with its WTO
obligations, "she said. "The EU must understand that as a result
of its failure to comply with its WTO obligations, the United
States will act firmly and swiftly under its WTO rights to sharply
raise tariffs on imports from the EU in an amount equivalent to
the trade damage."
</P>
<P>
In a press release here Monday, the United States claimed that
it would exercise its WTO rights by imposing 100 percent tariffs
on a list of EU products with an annual trade value of 116.8
million dollars. The list of products and other details regarding
the tariff increases will be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
The trade dispute over the EU's beef policies dates back to the
1980s. In December 1985, the EU adopted a directive on livestock
production restricting the use of natural hormones to therapeutic
purposes, banning the use of synthetic hormones, and prohibiting
imports of animals, and meat from animals, to which hormones had
been administered.
</P>
<P>
The WTO arbitrators also determined that Canada suffered a loss
of 11.3 million Canadian dollars (about 7.6 million U.S. dollars)
per year from the EU beef import policy.
</P>
<P>
According to the United States, on all occasions of the Food
and Drug Administration's testing, the six hormones subject to
this trade dispute have always been found to be safe.
</P>
<P>
In late December 1987, the United States announced an increase
in duties on selected European products in response to the EU
hormone directive and related measures, but immediately suspended
this action to promote a negotiated solution of the issue.
</P>
<P>
Following the entry into force of the WTO Agreement on the
Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures (SPS) on
January 1,1995, the United States and Canada filed complaints
against the EU's hormone-treated meat ban.
</P>
<P>
On August 18, 1997, a WTO dispute settlement panel issued its
report finding that the hormone ban is not based on scientific
evidence, a risk assessment, or relevant international standards
in contravention of the EU's obligations under the SPS agreement.
</P>
<P>
On February 13, 1998, the WTO dispute settlement body gave the
EU 15 months to implement WTO rulings. Complaining that the EU
took no actions to implement the WTO rulings by the deadline of
May 13,1999, the United States exercised its WTO rights by
requesting authorization to suspend tariff concessions on EU goods
with an annual trade value equivalent to annual lost exports of U.
S. beef, estimated by the United States as equal to 202 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The EU requested arbitration over the amount of lost U.S. beef
exports, insisting that the amount was only about 53 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
