<HEADLINE> Japan Welcomes Pakistan-India Accord on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan on Tuesday welcomed the latest
agreement reached by Pakistan and India aimed at ending the
conflict in the disputed Kashmir area.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura said he hopes the two
South Asian countries would quickly realize a cease-fire under
their weekend accord.
</P>
<P>
"We hope for an early end to the fighting, with both India and
Pakistan restoring the Line of Control," Komura told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India reached the agreement over the weekend to
restore the Line of Control, the de facto borderline in Kashmir
that divides the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Line of Control was established following an agreement
signed by the two countries in 1972, which also requires them to
resolve all disputes through bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Pakistan and India have been high since the
alleged intrusion of Pakistan-backed Muslim forces into the Indian-
controlled part of Kashmir in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
