<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Traditional Exports Grow in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's non-traditional exports
have registered the highest growth rates among all sectors
although the country's economic performance has somewhat been
negative for most of the past eight years, according to the
Exporter Audit of Export Board of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
While copper exports previously earned about 80 percent of the
country's foreign exchange revenue, the non-traditional exports
now are accounting for about 33.2 percent of its foreign exchange
earnings, said the newsletter issued by the export board available
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's exporting companies have increased from 188 in
1997 to 248 in 1998, the highest number of exporting firms since
1987, according to the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
On Zambia's export markets, the European Union continues to be
the major destination for its non-traditional exports accounting
for 34 percent of the total followed by the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) region with about 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has become one of the largest markets because of
the declining exports to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
due to the war in that country.
</P>
<P>
Constraints facing the non-traditional exports include lack of
access to export credit guarantee and export insurance scheme.
</P>
<P>
The Export Board of Zambia has urged the government to give
more incentives to exporters such as those contained in the 1993
Investment Act. The incentives have been removed.
</P>
<P>
Should all areas of concern be amended and the target of
increasing non-traditional exports to 400 million U.S. dollars
from current 300 million dollars be achieved, Zambia could within
a few years significantly reduce its dependence on copper exports,
said the Audit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
