<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Submits Niger-Delta Bill to Par't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
Monday officially presented the much desired Niger-Delta bill to
the National Assembly, parliament of the country, for
consideration and eventual passage into law before leaving for the
Algiers OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which Obasanjo promised in his tour to the
conflicting Warri region last month, was aimed at seeking a
fundamental solution to the crises raging in the oil rich southern
Niger delta for decades.
</P>
<P>
The bill proposes the setting up of a Niger-Delta Development
Commission to look into and manage the social development in the
region, where poverty is believed to be the main reason behind the
unrest. The unrest claimed hundreds of lives in the conflict in
Warri city and its environ last month.
</P>
<P>
Necessary objections, raised by the governors of Rivers,
Bayelsa, Cross Rivers, Akwa-Ibom, Edo and Ondo States, were
reflected in the bill, This Day newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The percentage to be contributed by the oil companies has been
moderately adjusted to reflect the realities on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all of the country's oil output yields in the region,
yet most people here are living on a tight margin, which
translates into hatred between different ethnic groups and
assaults on the foreign oil company staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
