<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Sell Public Stake in Joint Banks, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has decided to sell the public
stake in 15 joint banks and companies, the Egyptian Gazette
newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made on Monday during a meeting of the
Ministerial Committee on Privatization, headed by Prime Minister
Kamal El-Ganzouri, Minister of Cabinet Affairs Talaat Ahmed Hammad
said.
</P>
<P>
The committee approved the sale of the public stake in the
International Islamic Bank for Investment and Development, Banque
Misr-America and Egypt-Iran Bank, Hammad said, without mentioning
the amount of the public shares in the banks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt began to privatize 314 state-owned enterprises in 1995 in
a bid to upgrade the efficiency and competitiveness of the
enterprises. So far, more than one third of the selected have been
privatized.
</P>
<P>
But the government is cautious when it comes to the
privatization of the national banks for fear that the step may
give rise to financial turmoil. The would-be selling of the public
stake in joint banks appears to be a test in the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The privatization committee also ratified the selling of the
public shares in the Alexandria Company for Carbon Black in the
petrochemical industry, which is estimated at 134 million Egyptian
pounds (39.41 million U.S. dollars), or 8.9 percent of the
company's total capital, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed on the selling of Egypt's shares in the
Egyptian-Kuwaiti Company to the Kuwaiti partner. The public stake
in the Building and Reconstruction Company and the Egyptian
Agricultural Company for Seeds Production will also be sold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
