<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Farmers Call for Permits to Export Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambian farmers have called on the
government to allow them to export their maize to enable them to
meet their loan obligations, the Times of Zambia newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President of the Zambia National Farmers Union Ajay Vashee has
said that since the government will not buy local maize this year,
it should issue the farmers permits to export their maize to
neighboring countries,
</P>
<P>
The Zambian Food Reserve Agency does not have the required 50
billion kwacha (about 20 million U.S. dollars) to buy maize this
year because it has not recovered the money the farmers borrowed
in form of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has in turn refused to commit any more
money to the agency to enable it to buy maize.
</P>
<P>
Vashee said the food reserve agency should be held responsible
for the whole situation for acting irresponsibly by engaging in
unprofitable business of dishing out fertilizer to desperate
small-scale farmers and failing to buy local maize for strategic
reserve.
</P>
<P>
The union leader urged the agency to secure money to buy maize
to ensure price stability in local maize market.
</P>
<P>
The maize prices are dropping on the local markets because this
year farmers have produced more maize than demand.
</P>
<P>
Vashee said leaving the situation at its current position will
force the farmers to sell maize at give-away prices.
</P>
<P>
If the farmers do not meet their loan obligations, they will be
 subjected to no further funding from lending financial
institutions next season.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the government said that it is impossible for
it to find money to buy maize for strategic reserves because this
will put more pressure on the state budget of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
