<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Countries Consider Unified Traffic Penalties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
countries are considering a unified system of traffic penalties in
their efforts to stamp out reckless driving.
</P>
<P>
Under the planned system, if a driver registered in the United
Arab Emirate (UAE) commits an offense in any of the other five
countries, namely Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain,
the penalty will be imposed on him, the Gulf News daily reported
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A computer record will register where and when the offense
takes place and motorists who are repeatedly stopped for traffic
violations could lose their license.
</P>
<P>
According to UAE traffic department officials, the issue will
be discussed at the next annual meeting of GCC heads of traffic in
Saudi Arabia. The meeting was expected to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the system will help reduce road
accidents, which are a major cause of deaths in the region, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The officials also confirmed reports that the UAE will ban the
use of hand-held mobile phones while driving as of October 1.
</P>
<P>
Drivers who want to make phone calls on the road will have to
use hands-free sets, together with microphones and speakers, the
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
