<HEADLINE> S. African President Could Visit U.S. in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
has proposed informally that South African President Thabo Mbeki
visit Washington in August this year, the Business Day newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
No official invitation has been issued to avoid any appearance
of a snub should Mbeki demur, the paper said. However, the matter
is being discussed by diplomats in both countries. August 12 to
13 are the dates on offer.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here are worried that the proposal may be jumping the
gun, coming so soon after Mbeki's inauguration and at a time when
his first priority for official travel would logically be Africa,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. Congress is in recess in August, one U.S.
official said, Congress members would change their holiday plans
and return to Washington if Mbeki visited the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mbeki and U.S. Vice-President Al Gore are due to
meet in New York in late September when Mbeki attends the opening
of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is billed as an executive meeting of the U.S.-South
African Bi-national Commission. 
</P>
