<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 07:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon has Better Living, Lower Literacy: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese living standard measured
by real per-capita income improved to 5,940 U.S. dollars compared
with last year's 4,977 dollars, a United Nations report said.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star Tuesday quoted the report as saying that the
longevity in Lebanon rose from 69.3 years to 69.9. In addition,
the country's literacy dropped from 92.4 percent in 1998 to 84.4
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
In the ninth annual U.N. Human Development Report which listed
174 countries, Lebanon has dropped from 1998's 66 to 69 this year
in terms of life expectancy, educational attainment and adjusted
real income.
</P>
<P>
"It's the application of new measurements and data which
resulted in Lebanon's lower standing," said Yves de San, the
U.N.'s resident coordinator in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Had the same methodology and data been applied as last year,
Lebanon's ranking would have actually been 57. So, we are actually
better off this year," he added.
</P>
<P>
Canada topped the list for the sixth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
In the Middle East, Lebanon ranked higher than Jordan, Syria
and Egypt, but came behind Libya, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar,
Bahrain and Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
