<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Details Added China, Australia Conclude WTO Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China and Australia announced here
today that they have concluded bilateral negotiations on all
issues concerning China's admission into the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The two sides said in a joint press communique issued here that
they have "decided to conclude their overall bilateral
negotiations on China's accession to the WTO."
</P>
<P>
The joint press communique said that China and Australia
confirmed the outcome of bilateral WTO negotiations during
Australian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Trade Tim
Fischer's visit to China last May.
</P>
<P>
By announcing the conclusion of bilateral talks on China's WTO
accession, Australia has become the second major country, after
Japan, to complete bilateral WTO negotiations with China. Japan
and China announced the conclusion of their talks last Friday.
</P>
<P>
China's bid to enter the multi-lateral trade organization has
lasted for 13 years, and thus far China has completed bilateral
negotiations on WTO membership with a dozen member states.
</P>
<P>
China's bid made significant progress during Premier Zhu Rongji
's visit to the United States last spring when the U.S.
administration voiced firm support for China's entry into the WTO
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S.-led NATO's attack on the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade on May 8 resulted in a standstill of the talks between
China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S.-led missile attack against the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade has damaged the good atmosphere of negotiations. Only
after U.S.-led NATO has made a response satisfactory to China and
a good atmosphere is reinstated can talks be resumed," Trade
Minister Shi Guangsheng said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Firms Strive for Operating Tanzania's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 13 (Xinhua) - Five foreign companies are
contending for operating the Tanzania Harbors Authority's
container terminal, according to the Presidential Parastatal
Sector Reform Commission (PSRC).
</P>
<P>
The commission has invited all short-listed potential investors
to collect bidding documents and to submit technical bids by
September this year, the Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Chairman of the reform commission, John Rubambe, said
Monday that the winning bidder or consortium of bidders will lease
and operate the container terminal for a period of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The commission has pre-qualified five potential investors from
a list of eleven local and foreign companies which collected and
submitted the pre-qualification documents.
</P>
<P>
The five companies are: Terminal Contenedores de Barcelona of
Spain, Hutchison Port Holdings (Hong Kong), Britain's Mersey Docks
and Harbors Company, International Container Terminal Services Inc
(the Philippines), and A.P. Moller of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Under the privatization arrangements, the lease holder will be
required to market the container vigorously in addition to
developing the facility to keep pace with demand, and increase its
competitiveness, Rubambe said.
</P>
<P>
The lessee is also expected to promote the use of the container
terminal for the handling of transit cargo to neighboring
countries and to assist importers and exporters in arranging for
movement of their cargo, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform Commission
was set up in the 1992/93 fiscal year to coordinate the
divestiture of this east African country's parastatal sector.
</P>
<P>
The strategy for privatization of Tanzania Harbors Authority is
to turn it into a landlord port, which means the ownership of the
harbor is in the hands of the government but commercial operations
will be privatized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
