<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Muslim Intellectuals Support No Presidential Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The powerful Indonesian Muslim
Intellectuals Association (ICMI) does not back up any presidential
candidate, including incumbent President B.J. Habibie, ICMI
General Secretary Adi Sasono said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"ICMI did not give support to any candidate. There was also not
back-up statement," Adi said, referring to the ICMI's two-day
congress in Bandung, capital of West Java, last week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the ICMI's congress on Sunday, Acting
Chairman Achmad Tirtosudiro said the association's members believe
there is no better and more acceptable presidential candidate than
Habibie.
</P>
<P>
"But because ICMI is not a political party that can nominate a
person, the aspirations of its members are accommodated in the
chairman's note," Tirtosudiro said.
</P>
<P>
Before attending a hearing with the parliament commission V
here, Adi said the congress did not discussed Habibie's bid for
another term in office.
</P>
<P>
"ICMI alone, as a body, did not give support to any
presidential candidates," he added.
</P>
<P>
Initiated by students in Malang, East Java, in 1990, the
association's longtime chairman was Habibie. It developed rapidly
by soliciting the support of former president Soeharto and many
high-ranking officials. It was considered instrumental in the
entry of several close Habibie associates into Soeharto's
cabinets.
</P>
<P>
Habibie inherited the presidency on May 21 last year from
Soeharto following mass riots in Jakarta, which killed more than
1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
After the June 7 general election, Habibie has been nominated
for the 1999/2004 term of presidency by the ruling Golkar Party.
He is in competition with Megawati Soekarnoputri, leader of the
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (DPI-P) which has been in
lead in the vote counting.
</P>
<P>
The People's Consultative Assembly, the country's highest
decision-making body, will meet in November to elect the country's
next president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
