<HEADLINE> Symposium On International Humanitarian Law Opens (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China opened a symposium on
international humanitarian law today, marking the centennial
anniversary of the first Hague Peace Conference and the fiftieth
anniversary of the signing of four Geneva conventions on
humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Society of International Law, the Red Cross Society
of China, and the United Nations Association of the People's
Republic of China are co-sponsoring the three-day symposium.
</P>
<P>
"Today, we are here to mark the centennial anniversary of the
Hague Peace Conference and the fiftieth anniversary of the signing
of the four Geneva conventions, not only for their contributions
to international law and human progress, but also for their
principle of the peaceful settlement of international disputes and
international humanitarian law and relevance to contemporary
reality," said Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan in a written
speech read at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
It remains an important task for all governments and peoples of
the world to ensure strict observance of the principle of the
peaceful settlement of international disputes and effective
implementation of international humanitarian law with a view to
realizing universal and lasting international peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 26 countries, including China, gathered in
1899 in the Hague for a peace conference, creating a precedent for
regulating war and peace through the convocation of international
conferences and the formulation of international treaties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Symposium on International Humanitarian Law Opens (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Hague Peace Conference adopted the Hague Convention for the
Peaceful Settlement of International Disputes and the Hague
Convention Respecting the Laws and Customs of War on Land. They
thus laid a foundation for further efforts to ban wars through
international law and to establish principles and regimes for the
peaceful resolution of international disputes.
</P>
<P>
Fifty years ago, the famous Geneva Conference enacted the
historic Four Geneva Conventions, which further promoted the
development of humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
Despite certain inevitable limitations of this peace conference
and the two conventions, they reflected the strong desire of the
people of the world for peace and against war, and they also
represented a new starting point in the human effort to seek world
peace, said Xie Qimei, president of the United Nations Association
of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
"Though international law has made considerable progress in the
past 100 years, serious problems regarding violations of the
humanitarian spirit have occurred, and continue to occur, under
the banner of humanitarianism," Ma Jun, deputy president of the
Chinese International Law Association, said.
</P>
<P>
Experts and scholars from academic and research bodies and
relevant official organs are participating in the symposium.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats from Russia, the Netherlands and Switzerland, and
representatives from the United Nations Development Program
attended the opening ceremony of the symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
