<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Skids Down U.N. Human Development Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The sharp reduction in life
expectancy caused by HIV and AIDS has knocked South Africa down
the United Nations human development index ranking to 101st out of
174 countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Development Program (UNDP) said in its 1999 human
development report that although South Africa's overall ranking
declined, performance improved in almost all areas except life
expectancy.
</P>
<P>
It estimated that 51 percent of South Africans are not expected
to live to 60, compared with 11 percent of those living in
industrialized countries and an average of 28 percent for all
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The report, available here Tuesday, analyzed the changes in the
human development index, which ranks 174 countries in terms of
life expectancy, education and income.
</P>
<P>
It placed Canada, for the sixth consecutive year, on the top of
the list and Sierra Leone at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP cautioned that due to changes in methodology, it was
difficult to compare this year's and last year's rankings.
</P>
<P>
However, changes emphasized the effect on South Africa,
Botswana, Namibia, Zimbabwe and other countries in southern Africa
of rapidly declining life expectancy resulting from the impact of
HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Among African countries, only Libya is ranked ahead of South
Africa at the 65th, which falls immediately behind Albania, but
ahead of Indonesia, India, Azerbaijan and most African countries
including Zimbabwe, Tunisia, Egypt, Morocco and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
This year's report focused on the negative effects of
globalization and proposed mechanisms to bring "globalization back
on track" and "to make globalization work for people".
</P>
<P>
It showed widening disparities between developing and developed
 countries as well as the growing gap between rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
One fifth of the world's population living in the
highest-income countries have 86 percent of the world's gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The report called for measures to restructure and ensure
greater accountability of international institutions such as the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Trade Organization
(WTO), and to ensure that the developing countries have a more
effective voice in the WTO.
</P>
<P>
It also proposed that developing countries adopt regional
frameworks covering minimum labor and environmental standards to
help ensure protection "against the undermining influence of
global competition".
</P>
<P>
The UNDP insisted that the report, which backed IMF moves to
sell gold reserves to finance debt relief for poor countries, was
not an attempt to oppose globalization or Bretton Woods policies.
Its focus was to ensure that the benefits derived from
globalization were shared equitably. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
