<HEADLINE> First Arctic Expedition Draws Wide Attention in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, July 13 (Xinhua) -- As the Chinese ship Snow
Dragon carrying 124 scientists and journalists nears the Arctic
Circle, enthusiasm for China's first research expedition to the
North Pole is surging in the country.
</P>
<P>
More than twenty reporters representing 13 newspapers, news
agencies, and TV and radio stations are aboard ship and have been
transmitting a great many stories about the expedition.
</P>
<P>
This is China's first government-sponsored research expedition
to the Arctic, and signals a notable achievement for Chinese
scientific research, said Zhang Dengyi, director of the State
Oceanic Administration.
</P>
<P>
The research data gathered by the expedition will be collected
at the State Archives Bureau and the China Revolutionary Museum.
</P>
<P>
Experts say this Arctic research is of great importance to
China, as the Arctic region is believed to influence global
climate changes, and the data is expected to help China increase
the accuracy of its forecasting of floods and other natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
The popularization of oceanic knowledge has increased the
interest of the ordinary Chinese in the expedition. In a letter
written to a journalist aboard the Snow Dragon, one Chinese
citizen said that the spirit of exploration represented by this
North Pole voyage is the common treasure of the whole world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
