<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Islanders Lag Behind Rest of Population in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Pacific islanders in New
Zealand, like Maoris, are worse off in employment, income, health,
education and housing than the rest of the population and there is
little sign that things will get better, an official report
published here Tuesday shows.
</P>
<P>
The report by the Pacific Island Affairs Ministry of New
Zealand on the social and economic status of Pacific islanders
said there are significant gaps between islanders and the rest of
the population.
</P>
<P>
There is little indication that the position of Pacific Island
communities will get much better in key areas in the short to
medium term, it added.
</P>
<P>
"The urgency of these issues cannot be understated. Many areas
are in a state of crisis," the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Pacific islanders' unemployment in New
Zealand in 1996 was 15.3 percent, compared with 4.6 percent of
Europeans and 15.5 percent of Maoris.
</P>
<P>
Pacific islanders' median income in 1996 was 12,400 New Zealand
dollars (6,498 U.S. dollars), compared with 15,600 New Zealand
dollars (8,174 U.S. dollars) for the total population.
</P>
<P>
Pacific islanders also had the highest national rates of
meningococcal disease (11 times the rate for Europeans), measles,
rheumatic fever, heart disease, obesity, unplanned pregnancies and
abortion.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 26 percent of Pacific Island students left school with
no qualification, compared with 17 percent of non-Pacific
islanders.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 34 percent of overcrowded homes were occupied by
Pacific islanders, compared with 16 percent by Europeans and 40
percent by Maoris.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand has a population of about 3.8 million. Pacific
islanders make up 5 percent of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
