<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Refugees to Stay in Zambia Until Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Refugees in Zambia will not return
to Congo (K) until the cease-fire agreement signed in Lusaka last
Saturday is implemented.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) said
until the cease-fire accord is fully implemented, it would
continue to look after the refugees who fled the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) when conflict broke out there early last
August.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Daily Mail newspaper Tuesday quoted UNHCR assistant
program official Musango Kayombo as saying that although the
cease-fire pact had been signed, it was too early for the UNHCR to
consider repatriating the refugees because it was not clear
whether peace would be restored immediately.
</P>
<P>
Kayombo said that the UNHCR would only think of repatriating
the refugees when the restoration of peace in the third largest
African country becomes more certain.
</P>
<P>
"We are not in a hurry to send the refugees back to their
country. We would like to make sure that they are returning home
to peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kayombo said the UNHCR would visit affected places to assess
the situation and make sure that peace is in place before
repatriating the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are nearly 70,000 Congolese refugees in
Zambia, mainly in the provinces of North-Western, Luapula,
Northern and Western while Lusaka and the Copperbelt also host
some. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
