<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Enforce New Transport Rules Strictly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan police have impounded over
200 public service vehicles in its move to ensure that the
newly-introduced Transport Licensing Board (TLB) rules were
adhered to.
</P>
<P>
The country-wide crackdown on those defiant vehicles known as
"matatus" was taken shortly after a bus strike in protest against
TLB regulations which require a new license fizzled out Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's major newspapers reported Tuesday that more than 4,000
matatu owners in Kenyan capital Nairobi crowded government offices
to apply for the new certificates Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Traffic Commandant Samwel Angote issued a stern warning
that police countrywide will deal firmly with any private-owned
vehicles that would be found violating the TLB rules.
</P>
<P>
A three-month road license costs matatu owners 2,000 shillings
(about 28 U.S. dollars) and an annual license from 2,000 shillings
to 4,000 shillings (about 56 dollars), according to the TLB Act.
</P>
<P>
Matatu owners had complained that the new rules would put them
out of business.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenyan traffic authorities said that the fee for a new
license would cover advance tax, insurance fee and a public
service vehicle sticker, which enable matatu owners to compensate
victims of road accidents.
</P>
<P>
Just for the past two weeks, matatu-involved accidents have
reportedly claimed more than 30 lives in this east African
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
