<HEADLINE> World Cup Title Brings U.S. Women's Team $1 Million Bonus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- After winning the World Cup
trophy, the U.S. women's soccer squad won something really
tangible today: one million U.S. dollars cash.
</P>
<P>
In a thank you gesture for winning the cup, the U.S. Soccer
Federation is giving the team $1 million - up from $250,000.
</P>
<P>
The players were stunned. "We heard it might be hefty, but not
this much," forward Tiffeny Milbrett said.
</P>
<P>
Divided among 20 players, the amount comes to $50,000 a player.
Milbrett, however, said the team will vote shares to support
personnel, such as loyal intern Lori Spitler.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Soccer Federation President Robert Contiguglia said the
bonus was only right, because the tournament World Cup drew more
than 650,000 fans and made a surplus.
</P>
<P>
The players partied into the early hours Sunday but showed no
fatigue later in the day for events at Disneyland and in downtown
Los Angeles. They are in New York today, and all the talk shows
want them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
