<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets with Romanian Guest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang recalled his state visit to Romania in 1996, and said he
was deeply impressed by the warm hospitality he received there. He
also referred to Romanian President Emil Constantinescu's visit to
China in 1997, during which the two leaders held fruitful talks in
a candid and cordial atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 50th anniversary of diplomatic ties between
the two countries, and their friendship over half a century has
been deeply rooted in the hearts of the two peoples, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that bilateral cooperation in the political, economic,
and cultural fields have also expanded, and stressed this is not
only the common wish of the leaders of both countries, but also
the unanimous aspiration of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Jiang described Romania as one of China's important European
cooperative partners, and said China respects the development
course chosen by the Romanian people, and is willing to establish
a stable, long-term and comprehensive friendship geared to the
21st century and based on the principle of mutual respect,
equality, mutual benefit, and non-interference into each other's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Diaconescu, who is also chairman of the Romanian National
Peasants' Party, said the current visit, first ever for him, to
China has left him with a deep impression.
</P>
<P>
He said China is a friend of Romania, and although political
changes have taken place in Romania in recent years, its friendly
policy toward China remains intact. Romania is eager to continue
its friendship with China, which has been fostered through decades
of effort, and to strengthen bilateral cooperation and mutual
support in international affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
