<HEADLINE> China's Role Important to WTO: Australian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia believes that China will
"substantially strengthen the operation" of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) when it becomes member of the global trading
system, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said here today.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his departure for Shanghai at noon, Downer told a
press conference that Australia does see China's accession to the
WTO as a very important international objective in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Downer arrived in Beijing Sunday for a five-day official visit.
During his stay here, Chinese President Jiang Zemin met with him.
The Australian foreign minister also had separate talks with
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and Foreign Trade Minister
Shi Guangsheng.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied now with the terms of Sino-Australian
bilateral negotiations on China's accession to the WTO," Downer
said.
</P>
<P>
"This deal we have done with China will give Australia
substantial access to the Chinese market, and we believe that
China, as a member of the WTO, will substantially strengthen the
operation of the global trading system," he added.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the two countries exceeded five billion U.
S. dollars worth last year. Australia is China's 9th largest trade
partner, and China is Australia's 5th largest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
"I have been pleased with the visit, and I regard the visit as
a complete success," the Australian foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also extended a welcome to the approval by China to list
Australia as a destination for Chinese tourists, saying: "This
will lead to not only an upsurge in the number of tourists going
to Australia, but it will also help to develop the people-to-
people contacts and understanding between both peoples."
</P>
<P>
According to him, strong bilateral relationships are based on
mutual understanding between both governments and communities of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Australian foreign minister said the next round of human
rights dialog between the two countries is expected to take place
next month in Beijing. "We are very positive about the way the
dialog is developing," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
