<HEADLINE> Chinese Research Ship Navigation Guided by Satellite System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists will adopt
a satellite guidance system developed domestically to navigate a
Chinese research ship on the Arctic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The shipboard meteorological satellite processing system will
assist the Xuelong (Snow Dragon) Expedition Ship, carrying 124
scientists and journalists on an expedition to the North Pole, to
move along the correct route to the Pole.
</P>
<P>
The ship will soon enter the Arctic Ocean after a journey of
more than 3,560 nautical miles which began in Shanghai at the
beginning of July.
</P>
<P>
The system operators aboard the Xuelong can position themselves
at any moment according to cloud pictures transmitted by
meteorological satellites, explained Dr. Xie Simei, who led the
development of the system which was sponsored by the State Oceanic
Environmental Forecast Center and the China Aerospace Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Xie, who is also aboard to supervise meteorological and ice-
forecasting functions for the Xuelong's maiden voyage to the North
Pole, said the system is able to operate under adverse
circumstances, including as extremely high or low temperatures and
violent vibrations.
</P>
<P>
The system was proven effective during two expeditions to the
South Pole by Chinese scientists, helping the research ships to
shorten the voyages and save time and fuel, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to see a bright future for the application of the
system in China aboard several thousand ocean-going cargo vessels
and research ships," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
