<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gets 3.2b Dollars of Local Investment Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Board of Investment (BOI) of
Bangladesh received local investment offers amounting to around
155 billion taka (about 3.2 billion U.S. dollars) in the June
1996- June 1999 period, press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The offers were received against 4,230 projects in the period
with an estimated employment opportunities for more than 550,000
people, BOI sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rate of registration of the local investment with the BOI
during the three years grew 1.77 times over that of the five
previous years.
</P>
<P>
Now the BOI is conducting a survey on 2,695 projects registered
between June 1996 and June 1998 to assess the rate of
implementation, they said, adding that among the 1,094 projects
recently surveyed by the BOI, 438 projects are already in
operation, 112 are to go into production soon and the rest in
different phases of implementation.
</P>
<P>
The BOI sources attributed the increase to the facilitating
steps taken by the government to raise the local investment.
</P>
<P>
Banks and financial institutions disbursed long-term loans for
new industries to the tune of 7.98 billion taka (about 164.5
million dollars) in 1996, and the similar disbursement soared to
nearly 10.3 billion taka (about 212.4 million dollars) in 1997 and
11.4 billion taka (about 235.1 million dollars) in 1998, they
stated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has also permitted two banks to float
a government guaranteed bond and to sell bonds to mobilize
resources for industrial investment.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government has also taken up a 46-million-dollar
project for the development of the financial institutions with the
assistance of the World Bank, which will provide 40 million
dollars for industrial investment through the financial
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
