<HEADLINE> Thailand Begins Exporting Cattle to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- After decades of livestock import,
Thailand is now exporting Thai-bred cows to its Asian neighbors
and the first batch of cows has been shipped to Malaysia by truck,
the Bangkok Post said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chockchai Group of Thailand will deliver 200 heifers to
Malaysia this year, the newspaper quoted Choak Bulakul, president
of the group as saying.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia expects to import a total of 500 heifers from Thailand
in the near term.
</P>
<P>
Choak said Thailand has reached a stage where other countries
are recognizing the ability of Thai farmers as
international-standard producers of cows.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia has turned to Thailand rather than traditional
suppliers such as New Zealand and Australia because the animals in
Thailand are better suited to its tropical climate, environment
and farm management.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Thailand gains an export advantage due to cheaper
transport costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Choak suggested the government strengthen Thailand's position
as a key livestock supplier in the region.
</P>
<P>
Chochai Group's farm was the first in Asia that successfully
carried out embryo transfers in 1985.

=07130435
