<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-year-old Relics Unearthed in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
unearthed 180 valuable funeral objects while excavating a 2,000-
year-old tomb in north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The unearthed cultural relics include bronze and jade wares,
weapons, musical instruments, coins, and carriage parts dating the
Warring States Period (475-221 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists said that it is unusual to unearth such a
great number of items from a single tomb, which was protected by a
thick layer of anti-theft stone.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, discovered in Changzi county, is 12 meters under the
earth and is exquisitely designed. The corpse is in a fully rotten
state but the archaeologists have picked up a jade mask which is
believed to have been used for protecting the face of corpse.
</P>
<P>
The discovery is important for the study of the Warring States,
a chaotic period of time prior to the first unification of China
in 221 B.C., the archaeologists said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Raps Republicans Over Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The White House slammed
Republican lawmakers on Monday for proposing to cut taxes by some
800 billion dollars over the next decade, saying the proposals are
dangerous and potentially explosive.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton sent his top aides to criticize the
Republican proposals hours before he was to meet Republican Senate
majority leader Trent Lott, House Speaker Dennis Hastert and House
Majority Leader Dick Armey to discuss how to use 2.9 trillion
dollars in projected budget surpluses over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
"It's puzzling, disturbing and disappointing that the
Republicans now put forward a tax cut plan that leaves zero for
Medicare over a 10-year period," said Gene Sperling, who chairs
the White House's National Economic Council.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said America's prosperity
would be "put at risk by the dangerous reversal of course that
would be represented by huge tax cuts."
</P>
<P>
The proposals would swell the national debt, erode expected
budget surpluses and fail to provide money to meet existing
obligations, he said. "The tax cuts are potentially explosive."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Republican leaders questioned whether President
Clinton was looking for partisan fights rather than legislative
solutions.
</P>
<P>
"I'm still trying to figure out if he really wants to get
things done -- cooperate on Social Security, Medicare, taxes, even
trade -- or is he going to go the partisan route," Trent Lott said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans said Clinton is more interested in spending the
surpluses than in returning some of it to the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of criticisms between the two sides has soured
Clinton's meeting with the Republicans on Monday evening, which
was mainly to discuss Clinton's plans to reform Medicare that
offers health insurance to 38 million elderly Americans.
</P>
<P>
White House has proposed spending about 374 billion dollars on
Medicare, about 127 billion dollars more on defense and about 200
billion dollars more on other domestic programs, leaving 250
billion dollars for targeted tax cuts and 132 billion for interest
payments.
</P>
<P>
Republican proposals under discussion include a House plan to
cut taxes by 864 billion dollars over the next 10 years, chiefly
through a 10 percent reduction in income tax rates, and a Senate
plan to cut taxes by nearly 800 billion dollars over 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
