<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sixty Percent of Government Departments Open Websites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- About 60 percent of Chinese
government departments will go on-line this year, according to the
Ministry of Information Industry (MII).
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 720 government departments have opened Web
pages on the Internet to send out information about their
functions, programs, regulations and activities.
</P>
<P>
This represents a big step forward for the country's
information industry as well as for those government developments,
said an official with the MII.
</P>
<P>
The year 1999 is described as the year for government
departments to go onto the Internet. The idea of creating
electronic government was initiated by the China Telecom and the
State Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
"The move has improved efficiency, and increased political
transparency," said Wang Yuxin, from the China Telecom, the
backbone of Chinese information super-highway.
</P>
<P>
For a lot of Chinese on the street, it is still not an easy
thing to get across the guarded gate of a government compound in
Beijing. To reach the government through the Internet help unwrap
the mysteries.
</P>
<P>
The government departments that have opened websites include
ministries of the State Council such as the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Commission, as
well as provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education has opened on-line schools and the
Ministry of Labor and Social Security offers information on
employment through its portal.
</P>
<P>
Some ministry officials even make public their personal E-mail
addresses on the Internet to solicit public opinions.
</P>
<P>
According to the MII estimation, 80 percent of Chinese
government departments will have their own websites next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
