<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sues Toyota over Faulty Smog-control Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department
Monday charged Japanese automaker Toyota with putting faulty smog-
control computers on 2.2 million 1996-1998 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The department, on behalf of the Environmental Protection
Agency, filed a civil lawsuit against the Japanese company under
the Clean Air Act in U.S. District Court here, seeking to have the
computers repaired and the company fined up to 58.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit was filed after Toyota rejected a U.S. government
settlement offer last week that might have cost it 100 million
dollars in civil fines.
</P>
<P>
Toyota is the first automaker that has refused to settle a
Clean Air Act case with the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, Cadillac, Honda, Ford and seven heavy-duty diesel
engine makers have reached multimillion-dollar Clean Air Act
settlements with the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
"We're asking for an appropriate penalty and notifying the
court that the parameters are somewhere between zero and 58
billion dollars," said Joel Gross, chief of Justice's
environmental enforcement section.
</P>
<P>
In response to the lawsuit, Senior Vice President of Toyota
Motor Sales USA, the company's U.S. subsidiary in California, said,
"Toyota continues to be disappointed that despite our vehicles
having the best in-use emission performance in the industry, this
matter has not yet been resolved in a mutually agreeable manner."
</P>
<P>
He argued that regulators had reinterpreted their rules after
Toyota's equipment was approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
