<HEADLINE> Panama to Ask U.S. to Clean Military Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Panama's Foreign Minister
Jorge Eduardo Ritter said here Monday that his country will turn
to the world community for help in pressing the United States to
clean contaminated military bases in Panama.
</P>
<P>
Ritter said that Panama would go to international organizations
or forums for political support to press the United States to
ultimately take the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. authorities refused to clean up the polluted areas
with the excuse that no technology could serve this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian President Ernesto Perez Balladares had earlier urged
the United States to make reparations for material and human
damage caused by abandoned bombs in its former military bases.
</P>
<P>
Ritter noted that two decades back during the negotiations on
the Torrijos-Carter Treaties, Panama had received international
support for the complete withdrawal of American troops and the
hand-over of the inter-oceanic route of the Canal.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaties, United States should return the Canal to
Panama and pull out all its troops at midday of December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government bears moral and legal obligations to honor
these treaties, which anticipate the cleaning of the areas
contaminated by toxic substances and non-detonated munitions,
Ritter said.
</P>
<P>
The Torrijos-Carter treaties also contemplate the juridical
obligation of the United States to make reparations for the 21
victims of the explosions of abandoned bombs left by the U.S.
forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
