<HEADLINE> Hungary Wishes to Improve Ties with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Foreign Minister
Martonyi Janos said here on Monday that Hungary wishes to improve
and develop relations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after talks with visiting U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen, Janos said that the Hungarian-Russian
relations grew somewhat tense recently, but Hungary hopes that
tension will be gradually eased and relations be pulled back to
the normal track of development.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hungary is pleased with Russia's efforts in the
settlement of Kosovo crisis and believes that its bonds with
Russia will also grow in that direction.
</P>
<P>
The accession of Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic to the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization on March 12 caused great
discontent in Russia. Things grew worse on April 10 when Russia's
convoy carrying humanitarian goods for Yugoslavia was held for
more than 40 hours at the Hungary-Ukraine border, which evoked
strong protests from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Consequently Russia indefinitely postponed Hungarian Foreign
Minister's trip to Russia originally scheduled for late May.
</P>
<P>
In early July, Hungary closed its air space to six Russian
planes carrying Russian forces to join the international
peacekeeping operation in Kosovo, only to further strain the
already sour Hungarian-Russian relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
