<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Pledges to Promote Security in E.Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
constantly trying to promote peace in East Timor especially in the
run-up to the U.N.-run direct ballot on the future of the
territory, a ministerial delegation said Monday while visiting
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, consisting of 16 ministers led by Coordinating
Minister for Political Affairs Feisal Tanjung, flew in on Monday
for a one-day visit for talks with East Timor leaders and U.N.
representatives.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung said the success of the ballot rests on support from
all parties, including regional state agencies, social figures,
military, police and all components of the community in the
territory.
</P>
<P>
"President B.J. Habibie has given directives on how to conduct
the poll in a peaceful, orderly, honest and fair manner. To that
end, all concerned parties in East Timor should maintain a
conducive situation and keep alert against the possibility of
security disturbance detrimental to the whole process of the poll
and the credibility of Indonesia," the Antara News Agency Tuesday
quoted the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
The visit came two days after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
warned that poor security -- which is the responsibility of the
Indonesian police -- threatened the ballot.
</P>
<P>
Annan held that Indonesia is responsible for delaying the start
of the voter registration by three days from Tuesday. He said the
process would only begin on Friday if tangible improvements in
security were witnessed.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said the number of ministers in the
delegation "shows our government's determination, our sincerity
and our seriousness to really implement what we have agreed to do
on the basis of the New York agreement."
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in New York in May with the United
Nations, Indonesia and Portugal agreed that the East Timorese
would vote on August 8 on whether they accept an offer of broad
autonomy under Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
But last month Annan delayed the vote by two weeks, citing
logistical and security reasons. Annan will decide on Friday
whether the vote will go ahead as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
If the vote goes ahead, East Timorese will choose between
independence or autonomy within Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said everybody agreed the security situation is
continually improving and preparations for the ballot have been
going well.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Gen. Wiranto said the security forces would
play their part in keeping peace.
</P>
<P>
"The Indonesian government and its security apparatus will try
their best to create a conducive situation to enable registration
to run peacefully and smoothly," Wiranto added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. Deputy Special Envoy for East Timor Frances
Vandrell said after meeting Alatas that the Indonesian government
was giving serious attention to promoting peace in East Timor in
the run-up to the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
