<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Predict Plentiful Mines in West China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese scientists have
predicted that there are plentiful mineral resources in west China,
which has great potential to push the country's economy in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the mines was a result of the collision of
three continental plates 800 million years ago, which lifted
minerals 80 kilometers under the earth to a height that is ideal
for exploitation, according to scientists from the Tianjin
Geological and Mineral Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
"This is the most typical collision we have ever found since
the German developed the Continental Drift Theory early this
century," said Lu Songnian, who is responsible for the research
work.
</P>
<P>
He said that in a 900-km strip in Gansu Province and another
800-km one in Qinghai Province there bury more than a dozen
valuable minerals, including gold, bronze, zinc, lead, diamond and
jade.
</P>
<P>
"The finding will be significant for easing the anticipated
shortage of nonferrous metal resources which the Chinese economy
badly needs in the next century. It will also help for turn the
poverty-stricken western part into a flourishing region," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that detailed research is under way to unveil the
secrets of the mineral strips.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
