<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Uncovers 28m U.S. Dollars in Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's finance ministry had
uncovered 11,536 corruption cases involving 183.64 billion rupiah
(28 million U.S. dollars) from April 1997 to the end of last
month, The Jakarta Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Bambang Subianto said that more than 76
percent of the corruption was linked to tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
"These findings are related to the wrongdoing by various
parties," Bambang said.
</P>
<P>
Bambang, however, declined to disclose the names of those who
had either failed to pay taxes or were involved in tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had conducted further investigations
into 6,166 corruption cases covering 27.56 billion rupiah (4.2
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Bambang's announcement was part of the government's third-stage
report on the results of the national campaign against corruption,
collusion and nepotism, particularly during the 32 years of former
president Soeharto's rule.
</P>
<P>
Bambang said the government has revised various past
regulations which provided tax relief and other privileges to
certain institutions and companies.
</P>
<P>
The minister also announced new criteria on companies required
to submit annual financial reports to the government in a bid to
improve transparency and increase government tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Under the new regulation, companies which must submit annual
financial reports include those with minimum assets of 25 billion
rupiah (3.81 million dollars) or those which have bad debts at
local banks.
</P>
<P>
The government stipulated last year that companies with minimum
assets of 50 billion rupiah (7.62 million dollars) were required
to submit annual financial reports.
</P>
<P>
Bambang said foreign companies operating in Indonesia were also
obliged to submit annual financial reports.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory reporting would help the government build a
strong database in designing various policies including tax and
investment, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
