<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Mayon Volcano Causes 2 Earthquakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Mayon Volcano
caused two volcanic earthquakes and one short duration harmonic
tremor during the past 24 hours, the Philippine Institute of
Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report, the institute said that its instruments also
observed moderate steaming activities in the past observation
period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ground deformation measurements showed no unusual
volcano edifice change, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
In view of the foregoing observations, the institute reiterated
Alert Level 2 for the volcano, which is about 330 kilometers
southeast of Manila.
</P>
<P>
Alert Level 2 means the public should not venture inside the
delineated six-kilometer radius permanent danger zone and the
seven-kilometer safety buffer zone in the southeast sector.
</P>
<P>
The institute also warned residents near the footslopes of
Mayon to be aware of rockfall occurrences and the presence of
loose volcanic debris that may be transported downslope.
</P>
<P>
On June 22, Mayon's mild eruption rained ash over surrounding
towns of the volcano.
</P>
<P>
Mayon's last major eruption in 1993 killed 78 people and
affected 17,119 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
