<HEADLINE> Lanzhou Strengthens Car Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Lanzhou, capital city of Gansu
Province in northwest China has adopted tough measures to curb car
pollution in a campaign for cleaner air in the city.
</P>
<P>
Under an anti-pollution plan, new buses and taxies on the
streets now must use lead-free gasoline or liquefied petroleum gas
(LPG).
</P>
<P>
The new "blue sky" program also encourages old vehicles to
continue to use lead-free gasoline and get ready for renovation to
use LPG.
</P>
<P>
Currently five LPG stations are now under construction and a
number of enviroment-friendly cars have entered the city markets.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou used to be notorious for its poor air quality in winter
because of its unique geographic conditions and industrial
construction. The tremendous efforts over the past two decades
have greatly improved the air quality there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
