<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Reap 1.5 Percent GDP Growth for 1999: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 12 (Xinhua)-- Bulgaria may reap a GDP growth of 1.5
percent for 1999 as a result of its economic restructuring and the
current account deficit is likely to account for 5.5 percent of
GDP, said International Monetary Fund (IMF) mission official Juha
Kahkonen at a news conference here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission has completed its second review of the three-
year agreement with Bulgaria, under which some 280 million U.S.
dollars have been extended to Bulgaria since November 1998, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Board of Directors will discuss the results of the
review in September, and a favorable decision may be expected on
the floating of the fifth loan of 70 million U.S. dollars to the
Eastern Europe country, Kahkonen said.
</P>
<P>
A four to five percent GDP growth and an inflation below two
percent are expected for Bulgaria in 2000, Kahkonen said, adding
that a drop in the current account deficit is also projected.
</P>
<P>
The next review of the agreement and a discussion of the 2000
budget will be carried out in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
