<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Plans Air-Sea Surveillance For Economic Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
planning to set up a marine surveillance system covering its
entire Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) with the help of the navy and
the air force to combat illegal activities such as poaching, the
official Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries Minister Mahinda Rajapakse was quoted as saying that
the ministry was establishing a monitoring control system on the
sea using coast guards and patrol boats.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the system is to combat illegal activities such as
coral and sand mining and the use of illegal fishing gear and
methods, and to monitor the EEZ and prevent the illegal entry of
foreign fishing vessels, Rajapakse said at a meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the coastal surveillance will commence by
the end of this year. Already 100 recruits for the new service are
undergoing training.
</P>
<P>
The second phase for the entire EEZ will be implemented in the
year 2001 with the participation of the navy and air force, the
minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
