<HEADLINE> Mexican Cement Creates Subsidiary in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Cement, CEMEX,
announced on Monday its creation of a subsidiary in Asia, with an
initial capital of 950 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a communique, CEMEX, the largest cement company on the
American continent and one of the three biggest in the world, said
that CEMEX Asia Holdings (CAH), the new company, will have its own
capital of 800 million dollars, to which another 150 coming from a
group of institutional investors will be added.
</P>
<P>
Among them are Asian Infrastructure Fund II (AIG) and Special
Investments (GIC), the investment subsidiary of the Government of
Singapore Investment Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the new subsidiary is "to take advantage of
investment opportunities of cement assets in Asia", said the
communique.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement marks an important step in our financial
strategy designed to support CEMEX's negotiating plan in Asia,"
said Rodrigo Trevino, corporate financial director of this holding,
which has a production capacity of 61 million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
Trevino said that CEMEX will keep on "analyzing growth
opportunities" in Asia and the creation of CAH "will give
financial flexibility for continued attraction of investment
alternatives."
</P>
<P>
CEMEX's main partner in this new company, Asian Infrastructure
Fund II, has an asset of 1.7 billion dollars and has investments
in financial capital instruments in China, India, Korea, the
Philippines and Thailand, among other countries.
</P>
<P>
CEMEX, with subsidiaries on three continents, is also the
largest white cement maker in the world and the biggest
intentional seller of cement and clinker.  
</P>
</TEXT>
