<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warmer Climate Could Cause Ice And Snow In Northwestern China To Melt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Arid northwestern China could have
more water from glaciers in the next 50 years because of global
warming, Chinese scientists say, and this will be important for
China's strategy to develop the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
Water running off glaciers in northwestern China will increase
by 50 percent if the temperature rises one degree centigrade in
the next 40 years, according to Prof. Kang Ersi, of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences' Lanzhou Institute of Glaciology and
Cryopedology.
</P>
<P>
Kang has studied glaciers in the region for more than ten years
and says that, although the glaciers in the Northwest are
shrinking as a result of global warming, they are in the
hinterland and the change is not so apparent.
</P>
<P>
The change will not change by more than five percent by 2030,
but the water resources from melted snow and ice will gradually
increase, Kang says, and glaciers will help alleviate the aridity
in the Northwest and help the economic and social development and
environmental protection of the region.
</P>
<P>
China has the largest number of mountain glaciers at a low
latitude in the world, on a 58,000-sq.km. area. About 60 percent
of China's glaciers are in the Qilian, Tianshan, and Kunlun
Mountains in the Northwest and are a major water source of rivers
and underground water in the region. Over a billion cubic meters
of thawing water from glaciers on Qilian Mountain run into the
Shiyang, Shule, and Heihe rivers.
</P>
<P>
The Northwest, a priority in China's overall development plan,
is rich in natural resources, particularly land resources, but for
many years shortage of water has bottlenecked its economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
