<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican President Visits Guatemala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Costa Ricas President Miguel
Angel Rodriguez arrived Monday in Guatemala for a working visit.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that during the visit the Costa
Rican president and his Guatemalan counterpart Alvaro Arzu will
review bilateral issues and the Central American integration.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents will discuss the situation arising from the
Sunday earthquake in northwest Guatemala, which killed at least
one people and injured 32 others besides property damage.
</P>
<P>
The most affected zone by the quake of 6.1 degrees on the
Richter scale was Izabal department.
</P>
<P>
Spokespersons from Costa Rica's Foreign Ministry said that
Rodriguez and Arzu will also look into agreements designed to
regulate regional trade.
</P>
<P>
Central America has been passing through a difficult and slow
restructuring stage in its lengthy process of integration since
the five countries -- Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador
and Guatemala decided in 1991 to negotiate a new trade agreement
between them.
</P>
<P>
The process was affected in recent weeks by increasing tensions
between Costa Rica and Nicaragua due to a dispute over navigation
rights on the border river San Juan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
