<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Income from Crude Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's income from crude oil
increased by 500 million U.S. dollars in the first half of the
year owing to a rise in share prices of the commodity at an
international level, finance analysts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Specialists of the Mexican Financial Group BBV-Probursa said
the amount could offset the increase of public debt caused by the
rise of share prices by a quarter point in interest rates in the
United States last month.
</P>
<P>
In December 1998, Aztec crude price reached its lowest
historical level, fixing itself at 7.67 dollars per barrel, but it
rebounded in the past three months, with Mexico's mixture rated 15.
93 dollars at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
BBV-Probursa analysts attributed the hike of crude prices to a
reduction of stocktaking in the United States for the third
consecutive week and the climbing of carbides prices in the summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Returned overseas Chinese and relatives of overseas Chinese
have been called on to work for the prosperity and reunification
of China.
</P>
<P>
The call was jointly made yesterday by Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
and Chairman of the All-China Federation of Returned Overseas
Chinese Yang Taifang. They were speaking at the opening session of
the Sixth National Congress of Returned Overseas Chinese and
Relatives of Overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese and Australian leaders yesterday expressed their
wish to push bilateral relations forward.
</P>
<P>
More direct contacts and cooperation as well as an increase in
understanding between the two countries and peoples will promote
bilateral relations conducive to stability in the Asia-Pacific
region, President Jiang Zemin said at a meeting with Australian
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Leaders in Taiwan and of the Taiwan-based Straits Exchange
Foundation (SEF) were urged yesterday to stop sabotaging the cross-
Straits relations and contacts between the Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS) and SEF.
</P>
<P>
Tang Shubei, executive vice-president of ARATS, said in Hong
Kong yesterday that the "one China" principle is essential to the
stability of the cross-Straits relations and the cooperation
between ARATS and SEF, which reached a common understanding on the
"one China" principle.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese women's soccer team, who finished second in the
Third Women's World Cup in Los Angeles on Saturday returned to
Beijing in triumph and received rapturous welcome.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Finance is scheduled to launch an issue of
20 billion yuan (2.4 billion U.S. dollars) in treasury bonds today.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will target only financial institutions and can be
traded in the interbank borrowing system, the ministry said
yesterday in a press release.
</P>
<P>
-- China plans to establish a supervisory committee for the
state-owned commercial banks, Dai Xianglong, governor of the
People's Bank of China , said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The move is one of the measures to enable Chinese banks to
become more competitive as more foreign banks are licensed to
conduct business in China, Dai said at a press conference at the
Bank of International Settlements meeting in Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
