<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alesi Rules out Role as Schumacher Stand-in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Ex-Ferrari driver Jean Alesi on
Monday ruled out returning to the Italian Formula One team as a
temporary stand-in for injured former world champion Michael
Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
"I would love to race for Ferrari, but only if Michael was
there too," Alesi told Italy's RTL radio.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not interested in replacing him for these two months, it
really doesn't interest me at all," said Alesi, who drove for the
team from 1991 to 1995 when he was replaced by outspoken Briton
Eddie Irvine.
</P>
<P>
"Michael is a friend and I am fond of Ferrari, but I can't go
there under these conditions," added Alesi.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman, currently under contract with the Sauber team
which uses Ferrari-based engines, had been tipped by some as a
possible stand-in for the former world champion.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher broke his right leg on Sunday in a first lap crash
at the British Grand Prix and a Ferrari spokesman said he could be
out for six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
The injury means Schumacher's title hopes are over and Ferrari
are now looking to Briton Eddie Irvine, currently second equal in
the standings with Schumacher, to try and bring home their first
drivers' title since 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hatch Launches Presidential Election Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senator Orrin Hatch from
Utah made his first presidential campaign trip to New Hampshire
Monday, vowing to beat the Republican front-runner, Texas Governor
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
"There's no question that I've been in tougher circumstances,
no question that I've had to fight the establishment in Washington
and there's no question I've been able to bring people together,"
he said in New Hampshire, which holds the nation's first primary.
</P>
<P>
Describing himself as the more experienced candidate and the
candidate of the people, Hatch, a 22-year veteran of the Senate,
said he could beat the Texas governor with only 12 million
dollars to 15 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hatch noted his own experience, including his past chairmanship
of the Senate Labor Committee and his current chairmanship of the
Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said a key reason for entering the already-crowded
presidential race was Bush's rapid ascent in the polls and his
success in fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
"Money should not decide elections. It ought to be ideas," he
said.
</P>
<P>
With Hatch's participation, a total of 12 presidential
hopefuls are competing for the Republican nomination for
presidential candidate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
