<HEADLINE> U.S. Encouraged by Israeli-Palestinian Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday that the first summit between Israel and the Palestinians
was encouraging and positive.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat held talks on Sunday at the Erez Crossing between Israel
and the Gaza Strip. And the two leaders emerged with handshaking
after the meeting, promising to work together for peace.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister of Israel and the chairman of the
Palestine Authority have just had a very successful positive
meeting (and) pledged each of them to move forward together on
the peace process ... We were very encouraged," State Department
spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Barak will come to Washington on Wednesday amid high hopes
for quick progress in the Middle East peace process. He will see
President Bill clinton on Thursday and again on Monday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart, speaking earlier on
Monday, said the United States expected both Israel and the
Palestinians to live up to the commitments they have made at the
Wye River talks in Maryland last October.  
</P>
