<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Universiade Record Broken in Penultimate-Day Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 12 (Xinhua) -- On the penultimate day of the
fortnight Palma Universiade, Romanian Ionela Tirlea broke a 10-
year-old games record to take the women's 400-meter title here
Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old woman surged ahead from the start to finish in
49.88 seconds, beating the previous games record of 50.01 seconds
set by Anna Quirot of Cuba in Duisburg in 1989.
</P>
<P>
And Romania also became the only country that run home with
double golds from the athletics as Nicoleta Grasu threw to the
longest distance of 65.21 meters to claim the women's discus title.
</P>
<P>
The other six athletics finals of the day ushered in the
champions of six different countries with Ukrainian Dxexiy
Lukashevych claiming the day's first title by winning the men's
long jump in 8.16 meters in his second attempt.
</P>
<P>
The men's 400-meter final was won by American Jerome Davis in
44.91 seconds, Russian Joulia Taranova claimed the women's 800
meters in 1:59.63 and Jose Martinez of Spain clocked the fastest
of 29:37.56 to take the men's 10,000 meters event.
</P>
<P>
The decathlon title was won by Raul Duany of Cuba with a total
point of 8,050 while the day's last athletics title was won by
Pawel Januszewski of Poland who triumphed in the men's 400-meter
hurdles in 48.64 seconds.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the athletics competitions will produce the last
nine gold medals of the 20th Universiade.
</P>
<P>
The judo competitions concluded on Monday with France took the
women's team title and South Korea triumphed in the men's team
event.
</P>
<P>
Of the 18 judo titles at stake, France, Cuba and Japan had the
most of three gold medals each, both China and the Netherlands got
two apiece, leaving the other five to be split by Puerto Rico,
Canada, Mongolia, Romania and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
In the last event of the men's team final, South Korea claimed
its first judo title by beating Spain, with the bronze medal
shared by Japan and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
France defeated Cuba for the women's team title with South
Korea and Italy shared the bronze medal this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In the women's basketball final, hosts Spain stunned the
Americans in a low-scoring final 57-48 as two cagers from either
side scored in double digits. Russia outscored Ukraine 77-71 to
take the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
The Americans eventually took the men's basketball title by
beating Yugoslavia 79-65 as they dominated the rebounds by 31
against 23, despite Yugoslavian M. Sekularac, with a height of 2.
03 meters, scored 31 points alone.
</P>
<P>
Spain claimed the bronze medal by beating Mexico 90-78 as they
outscored the visitors by 10 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
In water polo, Spain beat Italy 6-5 to claim the championship
with the United States taking the bronze medal after its 13-7
victory over Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Cuba finished fifth by beating Yugoslavia 6-5 while Russia took
the seventh place by downing Canada 7-5, followed by Greece,
France, Australia, New Zealand, Kazakhstan, Brazil and Japan.
</P>
<P>
In the day's last final of the soccer tournament, Spain scored
the golden goal by F. Soriano in the second half of the extra time
from a corner kick to beat Italy 2-1 for the most coveted team
title of the Universiade.
</P>
<P>
Brazil took the bronze medal by beating the Czech Republic 5-4
in penalty kicks after both sides tied 2-2 in regular time, Iran
placed fifth by beating South Korea 3-2, and Mexico overcame
Morocco 2-1 for the seventh place.
</P>
<P>
Britain beat Uraguay four goals against nil to finish ninth,
with Ukraine placed 11th after beating Ireland 3-2 in penalty
kicks after both sides scored two goals each in the 120-minute
competition.
</P>
<P>
Japan also won the penalty kicks 3-1 against Nigeria from a 1-1
draw to finish 13th place, while Australia tailed in the 15-member
tournament as South Africa skipped due to financial problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Internal Debt Rises 51 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 12 (Xinhua)-- Costa Rica's internal debt
reached at the end of June 1999 to 3.538 billion U.S.dollars, or
51 percent increase in the last 12 months (July 98-June 99), the
Central Bank said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of this amount, 2.572 billion dollars correspond to the debt of
the government and 966.6 million dollars to the Central Bank.
Statistics show that in the past 7 years, from December 1992 to
December 1998, Costa Rica's internal debt grew by 408 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
