<DOCNO> XIE19990713.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher 'Comfortable' in Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Ferrari team driver Michael
Schumacher is in a "comfortable" condition at hospital after
breaking his right leg in Sunday's British Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
But the German will have to stay a second night at Northampton
General Hospital, whose chief executive David Wilson gave further
details at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old was airlifted to the hospital from the nearby
Silverstone circuit to have several metal pins inserted into the
leg to hold the broken bones in place.
</P>
<P>
The hospital chief said the surgery had been successful and
that the Ferrari driver was due to begin physiotherapy.
</P>
<P>
"Michael Schumacher had a comfortable night. He is taking
fluids and had a good breakfast," said Wilson on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"His wounds are healing well and he is moving his legs.
</P>
<P>
"He will stay at the hospital at least until tomorrow," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher is regarded as one of the fittest drivers in Formula
One racing, but is still likely to miss the next six weeks of
action, including three Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
However Ferrari manager Jean Todt told the news conference that
the accident could have been far worse.
</P>
<P>
"Michael was lucky just to break his right leg," said the
Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
"A few years ago I would have feared the worst for him but
thanks to all the safety improvements over the past few years his
injury was not as bad as it would have been then."
</P>
<P>
Schumacher's Ferrari left the track on a bend and slammed into
a tyre barrier at more than 200 kph.
</P>
<P>
Todt is confident his No one driver will return before the end
of the season, even if the team are still unsure of the exact
reason behind the accident.
</P>
<P>
"He has a good spirit," he said. "We don't know precisely what
happened yet. It was probably he had a brake problem but we have
to investigate."
</P>
<P>
But Todt refused to give further details about who would drive
Schumacher's car during his absence and suggested that an
announcement would be made later in the week.
</P>
<P>
"Luca Badoer is testing for us today, but that was already
planned, and then we will do some more testing on Tuesday before
making a decision," he said.
</P>
<P>
Badoer drives races for the small Minardi team, but is
contracted to Ferrari as their test driver.
</P>
<P>
Despite the setback, Todt refused to give up hopes of a first
drivers championship for the team since 1979.
</P>
<P>
"Eddie Irvine has shown he can win races and he could prove
more than a match for Mika Hakkinen," said Todt.
</P>
<P>
Irvine finished second in Sunday's race and is now eight points
behind championship leader Hakkinen, who did not finish.
</P>
<P>
After the accident Irvine joined with race winner David
Coulthard to criticise safety at the Silverstone track.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher's car skimmed the surface of a gravel trap and
crashed heavily into a tyre wall, with both safety features
failing to dramatically reduce the Ferrari's speed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Damon Hill is under pressure to decide whether he is
continuing his Grand Prix career until the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
Hill finished fifth in Sunday's race but his Jordan team need
to know whether he is ending his career now, or at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
The Silverstone-based team begin a three-day test in Italy on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If Hill does decide to retire, Formula 3000 driver Nick
Heidfeld has been lined up as a replacement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
