<HEADLINE> Romanian Claims 400m Title in Universiade Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Ionela Tirlea broke
a 10-year-old games record to take the women's 400-meter title
here Monday evening at the 20th University Games.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian woman, born in 1976, led from the start to finish
in 49.88 seconds, surpassing the previous games record of 50.01
seconds set by Anna Quirot of Cuba in Duisburg in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The silver medal was won by Mikele Barber of the United States
who clocked 51.03, ahead of Nigerian Doris Jacob in 51.04.
</P>
<P>
Tirlea's woman compatriot Nicoleta Grasu scored the longest
throw of 65.21 meters in her sixth attempt to claim the women's
discus for the second gold medal for Romania, wherein Joanna
Wisniewska of Poland finished a distance second in 63.97, ahead of
Brazilian Elisangela Adriano in 62.23.
</P>
<P>
Romania became the only country that run home with double golds,
as the other six gold medals of the day ushered in the champions
of six different countries.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian Dxexiy Lukashevych claimed the day's first track and
field title by winning the men's long jump in 8.16 meters in his
second attempt, beating Cuban Luis Felipe Melis and Erik Nijs of
Belgium to second and third in 8.05 and 7.99 meters respectively.
</P>
<P>
The men's 400-meter final was by American Jerome Davis in 44.91
seconds, with Paston Coke of Jamaica finished second in 45.15 and
J.Van Oudtshoorn of South Africa in third in 45.21.
</P>
<P>
Russian Joulia Taranova claimed the women's 800 meters in 1:59.
63 while Jose Martinez of Spain took the men's 10,000 meters in 29:
37.56.
</P>
<P>
Brigita Langerholc of Slovenia finished second in the 800
meters in 1:59.87 with Romanian Elena Buhaianu in third in 2:00.26,
and Naoki Mishiro of Japan claimed the silver medal in the 10,000
meters in 29:39.14, ahead of another Spaniard Pedro Trejo in 29:47.
27.
</P>
<P>
The decathlon title was won by Raul Duany of Cuba with a total
point of 8,050, beating American Stephen Moore to second in 8,028
and Benjamin Jensen of Norway to third in 7,982.
</P>
<P>
The day's last athletics title was won by Pawel Januszewski of
Poland who triumphed in the men's 400-meter hurdles in 48.64
seconds, with American Bayano Kamani finished second in 48.74 and
Swiss Marcel Schelbert third in 48.77.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the athletics competitions will produce the last
nine gold medals of the Universiade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
