<HEADLINE> China Takes Two Judo Titles in Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 12 (Xinhua) -- China failed to take the
women's team title but still wounded up with two crowns as the
judo tournament concluded here Monday afternoon at the 20th
University Games.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Hua, 25, took the first judo title by taking the women's
over 78-kg and triumphed again in the women's open category, all
the way by ippon.
</P>
<P>
"Yuan Hua is one of our best judokas in the category which
China enjoys traditional advantages through Gao Fenglian, Zhuang
Xiaoyan and Sun Fuming," said Fu Guoyi, coach of the Chinese judo
delegation.
</P>
<P>
"It's great that Yuan Hua has won two titles, but from a coach'
s view, I had hoped for more medals through different judokas,
which justify a team's overall level," said Fu.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the two gold medals, the Chinese judokas also reapt
one silver medal through Zheng Linli in the women's 57-kg class
and two fifth-place finishes in the women's 48-kg and 70-kg
categories through Zhao Shunxin and Du Min respectively.
</P>
<P>
"Both Zhao and Du just made their debut in the world arena,
they had won a string of matches in the repechage, an encouraging
sign for our Chinese coaches," Fu said.
</P>
<P>
"From the Universiade which featured most of the world best
judokas, we have trained our young athletes in the small classes,
found the differences for our second-string judokas in the middle
classes and strengthened our confidence in the over 78-kg and open
classes," the Chinese coach summoned.
</P>
<P>
"We have achieved progresses in the small categories, meanwhile
are well aware of the tough challenges ahead from both Japan and
South Korea in Asia," Fu said.
</P>
<P>
Of the other 16 judo titles including the men's and women's
team titles, France, Cuba and Japan had the most of three gold
medals each, the Netherlands got two, leaving the other five to be
split by Puerto Rico, Canada, Mongolia, Romania and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
In the last event of the men's team final, South Korea claimed
its first judo title by beating Spain, with the bronze medal to be
shared by Japan and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
France defeated Cuba for the women's team title with South
Korea and Italy shared the bronze medal this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The other two titles for France were through Lebrun Celine in
the women's 78-kg class and Douma Yacine in the men's 60-kg
category.
</P>
<P>
Cuba scored its three golds all by their women judokas as
Sivelis Verones won the 70-kg, Gonzalez Driulus in the 57-kg and
Verdecia Legna in the 52-kg.
</P>
<P>
Muneta Yasuyuji and Omigavi Michiro awarded Japan two men's
titles in the over 100-kg and 66-kg classes with Nagai Atsuko
triumphed in the women's 48-kg category.
</P>
<P>
Danielle Vriezema got the women's 63-kg title for the
Netherlands who won its second gold medal through Edwin Steringa
in the men's 81-kg class.
</P>
<P>
Soares Pedro of Puerto Rico won the men's 100-kg category,
Keith Morgani awarded Canada's its sole gold in the men's 90-kg
class, Boldbatar Khalig of Mongolia scored the top honour in the
men's 73-kg title while Alexandrl Lungu won the men's open class
for Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
