<HEADLINE> Brown to Sue over 'Bigot' Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Scotland football coach Craig Brown
has repeated his emphatic denial of allegations of religious
bigotry and said he will take legal action to clear his name.
</P>
<P>
The News of the World reported that Mr Brown, 59, was recorded
singing "hate-filled anti-Catholic" songs on an answerphone
message to his girlfriend, following an Old Firm match between
Glasgow rivals Rangers and Celtic.
</P>
<P>
And he declared: "I'm not going to resign because of an untrue
allegation."
</P>
<P>
He told BBC Radio Scotland: "I find it preposterous that I
could be accused of religious bigotry because there is not an
ounce of bigotry in me."
</P>
<P>
Mr Brown has been working in London but said he had an
appointment to see his solicitor when he returned to Glasgow,
after which he would make a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Any alleged songs or tape will be discussed when this
situation goes further and I don't wish to extend on that," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"But I wish to totally and completely refute any suggestion of
bigotry and I would defy anyone with whom I've worked in football
for 40 years or anyone who knows me, to make that accusation.
</P>
<P>
"I would say to you that there is not an ounce of bigotry in me
and that's emphatic and I think that could easily be proved and I
will be happily extending my attempt to prove that."
</P>
<P>
Asked if he was concerned about his reputation, Mr Brown said:
"Anything that's detrimental concerns you a little but I worry
more about the truth and I know the truth therefore I don't have
that inner worry, I can assure you."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday Mr Brown, a former player with Glasgow Rangers who
has been Scotland coach since 1993, said he intended to take legal
action.
</P>
<P>
"I have already taken legal advice and will have a full
consultation at the beginning of the week with a view to issuing
legal proceedings against the News of the World for defamation,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
