<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Compensates for Banning Canadian Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (WTO)
has ruled the European Union (EU) pay 11.3 million Canadian
dollars (about 7.68 million U.S. dollars) in compensation for
banning Canadian beef.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Trade Minister Sergio Marchi Monday confirmed
reception of the WTO arbitration, saying it "vindicates Canada's
position that the EU ban is arbitrary and unjustified."
</P>
<P>
But the minister held the compensation as less than asked for.
"Obviously, we wish the award had been higher," said Marchi.
</P>
<P>
The minister also warned that Canada would move to retaliation
if EU failed to honor the compensation ruling quickly.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the Canadian government will announce the
final list of EU products to be subjected to tariff increases,
unless EU lifts the ban imposed since 1989, according to official
sources.
</P>
<P>
Canada has recently requested authority from the WTO Dispute
Settlement Body to retaliate against EU, saying EU is baseless in
judging Canadian beef to be produced with growth hormones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
