<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Issue First Plastic Banknote to Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Romania's National Bank (central
bank) Monday announced that it would soon issue a plastic 2000 lei
banknote, worth about 12 U.S. cents, to mark the August 11 total
sun eclipse and the millennium.
</P>
<P>
The new banknote, to be launched on August 2, will be the first
in Europe to be made of plastic. Around 50 million banknotes are
to be issued on the occasion in this east-European country with a
population of 22 millions.
</P>
<P>
The banknote will depict the solar system on the recto side
with the Sun represented on the left, mentioning the total sun
eclipse in August. The verso side of the note will depict
Romania's map in the colors of the red, yellow and blue national
flag, marking the country's area where the sun eclipse will be
best seen.
</P>
<P>
Romania is considered to be the main attraction point for the
viewing of the eclipse, the point of most visibility of the
eclipse being situated very close to Ramnicu-Valcea town of
southern Romania. Bucharest will be the only European capital city
to be right in the center of the totality path and also has the
only solar telescope in Europe that can be used during the
eclipse.
</P>
<P>
More than ten countries worldwide are currently issuing such
plastic notes, which were first used in Australia 12 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
