<HEADLINE> Semiconductor Equipment Companies Showing Optimism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ENGELES, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Semiconductor equipment
companies worldwide are showing increasing optimism about
prospects for business, expecting the industry to grow nine
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
This means semiconductor equipment sales in 1999 will reach
23.8 billion U.S. dollars, according to a report released Monday
by Semiconductor Equipment and Materials International (SEMI), a
California-based international trade association.
</P>
<P>
SEMI conducted a survey among 85 of its member companies in the
United States, Europe and Japan. Respondents represent about 80
percent of the total sales volume for the global semiconductor
equipment industry. Industry optimism carries into predictions for
2000 and 2001, with annual increases of 18.3 and 21.8 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
By product category, the survey results indicate sales of wafer
process equipment should rise to 15.6 billion dollars in 1999, 9.8
percent above the 14.2 billion dollars in sales posted in 1998.
Sales of assembly and packaging equipment are expected to increase
to 1.7 billion dollars, up 13.3 percent from sales in 1998. Test
equipment sales should reach 4.6 billion dollars, up 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The results of this survey express renewed confidence among
equipment manufacturers about the prospects for growth in the
semiconductor industry," SEMI quoted its president Stanley Myers
as saying. "Our members are well-positioned to benefit from the
introduction of advanced semiconductor manufacturing technology as
well as from the continued expansion of new applications for
semiconductors."
</P>
<P>
Semiconductor capital equipment market worldwide stood at 21.8
billion dollars in 1998, down almost 21 percent from a year ago.
The ongoing industry recovery will result in global sales of 28.1
billion dollars in 2000 and 34.3 billion dollars in 2001,
according to SEMI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
